<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Speaks On Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Vice-premier Li Lanqing today
said that education can not only help lift China's vast rural
areas out of poverty, but can prepare the country for the
opportunities and challenges of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Li was winding up an inspection tour of east China's Fujian
Province that started on January 16, where he visited a number of
primary and secondary schools, universities, and vocational and
technical schools.
</P>
<P>
At a rural primary school where facilities were not very good
but where students are said to be first-class, Li said what is
really important for the quality of education are a good
headmaster and a team of qualified teachers.
</P>
<P>
"Poor areas will have greater hope to overcome poverty if
education there is highly developed," he stated.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with college and university faculty members, Li
told the participants that, while the government will increase
financing for education in keeping with the law, it is also
essential for schools to tap their own "potential".
</P>
<P>
"Existing education resources should be fully utilized and
reasonably distributed, and schools must make every effort to
increase efficiency and the quality of education," he noted,
urging institutions of higher education to change concepts, and
align themselves more with economic construction and social
development.
</P>
<P>
Li also stressed the necessity of setting up more vocational
colleges, improving ideological and political education in higher
education institutions, and paying more attention to improving
teachers' work and living conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
