<HEADLINE> Shortage of School Places Lamented in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's opposition United
Parties (UP) today said the government should channel more
resources toward construction of more schools in Harare to reduce
the current shortage of places in the capital.
</P>
<P>
UP Information Secretary Isaac Manyemba said the current
shortage of vacancies is due to gross misallocation of government
resources, adding that funds should be redirected from the
Ministry of Defense budget to finance infrastructural development
in schools.
</P>
<P>
He said as a result of the shortage, some headmasters are now
accepting bribes for places.
</P>
<P>
''The scarcity of both primary and secondary schools which has
caused a critical shortage of grade one and form one places is
because of the deliberate misallocation of government resources
and corruption,'' he claimed.
</P>
<P>
''This uncalled for shortage of places has intensified the
culture of corruption in the Ministry of Education as many
parents are being forced to pay headmasters and other influential
government officials bribes so that their children can be
admitted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Manyemba was commenting on reports that scores of children had
not found places in a number of Harare schools when the new
school year started last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
