<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Premier Lobbies for St Petersburg Olympic Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin joined government and Russian Olympic officials over
the past two days urging International Olympic Committee president
Juan Antonio Samaranch to award the 2004 Games to St Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
According to a report here, at a news conference on Sunday,
Samaranch said the Russian premier had "insistently laid out the
arguments for St Petersburg".
</P>
<P>
Russia's former capital, an industrial city of five million, is
one of 11 candidates vying for the 2004 Games. The others are
Rome, Cape Town, Stockholm, Rio de Janeiro, San Juan, Buenos
Aires, Athens, Lille, Seville and Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
"St Petersburg is a legendary city, world famous and very
beautiful," Samaranch said. "In 2004, I will no longer be IOC
president but, if I am living, I will gladly come to St Petersburg
for the Olympic Games." 
</P>
</TEXT>
