<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-19 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat: Hebron Is Liberated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEBRON, January 19 (Xinhua) -- "I announce Hebron as a
liberated city." Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat spoke to some 60,000 jubilant Palestinians in a
gathering here.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here today in his first official visit to
celebrate the withdrawal of Israeli troops from most of the city
which was under Israel's rule for the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
"The will of peace has succeeded," said Arafat in his emotional
address.
</P>
<P>
He hailed the Hebron deal reached with Israelis last week as
"the decision of peace" which means "a new thing in the Middle
East."
</P>
<P>
He expressed his optimism towards the peace process, saying
"together (with all peace forces in Israel), we can make the just
and durable peace in the Middle East."
</P>
<P>
Arafat thanked some world leaders in helping reach the
agreement, mentioning the names of U.S. President Bill Clinton,
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Jordanian King Hussein. He
also praised Europe's role.
</P>
<P>
In assessing the signing of Hebron accord, the PNA leader
asserted, "Hebron is a start for what is after Hebron" and "for
founding our independent Palestinian state."
</P>
<P>
He urged the Palestinians to shoulder the "great
responsibility to continue together and build together this great
construction of the Palestinian independent state."
</P>
<P>
"I say they have committed to their obligations, and we will
commit to all of our obligations decided by the agreement," he
added.
</P>
<P>
On future possible confrontation between the 200,000
Palestinians and the 450 Jewish settlers in the city, Arafat said,
"I tell the settlers in Hebron that we do not want any
confrontation.... I say to them that we are also with the just
peace."
</P>
<P>
In the speech he stressed that the just and comprehensive
peace is not only with Egypt, Jordan and Palestine, yet also with
Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In regard with the prospect of the peace process, the PNA
leader pointed out, "A long way is still in front of us with many
obstacles. I do not tell you that the land is furnished with
flowers." He called the Palestinians to proceed until the
independent state is established.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed national unity, describing it as "the
guarantee of our triumph, and the guarantee to proceed in our way
and establish the Palestinian independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
