<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, January 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- American Balloonist Steve Fossett's ground crew
in Chicago said that he was expected to land in either India or
Bangladesh at about 0700 GMT Monday. Fossett's support team says
the balloon does not have enough fuel to complete the
around-world-nonstop trip. He began his trip Monday in St. Louis
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- An Iraqi newspaper Sunday accused the United States
of using uranium projectiles against Iraqi army during the Gulf
War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
In an article marking the 6th anniversary of the Gulf War, the
Baghdad Observer quoted a secret report released by Britain's
Atomic Energy Authority as saying that uranium was used in attacks
against Iraqi vehicles by U.S. and British tanks in the 1991 war.
</P>
<P>
HEBRON -- Palestinian National Authority President Yasser
Arafat Sunday paid a victorious visit to Hebron with a strong call
for continued fight for Palestinian independence.
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Two campuses of the University of Nigeria Nsukka were
closed on Saturday after students destroyed properties during a
violent protest.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The United States has signaled that it will not issue
an entry visa to Gerry Adams, the leader of the political wing
Sinn Fein of the Irish Republican Army (IRA), until the IRA
reinstates its ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Prime Minister of the Republic of Vanuatu Rialuth
Serge Vohor arrived here Sunday afternoon for a six-day official
visit at the invitation of Chinese Premier Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
SOFIA -- Bulgaria's new president Petar Stoianov was sworn in
Sunday and vowed to hold dialogues with various political forces
to tide over the economic difficulties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
