<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Discussion Of Handling Existing Laws In Hong Kong (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The law panel of the
Preparatory Committee for the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) discussed handling the issue of laws in force in Hong
Kong, in Beijing during its Seventh meeting January 18 and 19.
</P>
<P>
The participants held that only a few ordinances, subordinate
legislation of laws previously in force in Hong Kong, which
totally or partially contravene the Basic Law, cannot be adopted
as laws of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
Most of the existing laws can be adopted as laws of the Hong
Kong SAR. But, when they are applied in Hong Kong, interpretation
should be made according to Hong Kong's status and the
stipulations of the Basic Law, after China resumes the exercise of
its sovereignty over Hong Kong and all improper terms or phrases
appearing in laws will be amended.
</P>
<P>
The participants said that ordinances previously in force in
Hong Kong that totally contravene the Basic Law are mainly laws
supporting Britain's colonial rule, such as the Application of
English Law Ordinance, a marriage law outside Britain, the British
Nationality (miscellaneous provision) Ordinance, the Secretary of
State for Defence (succession to property) Ordinance, the Royal HK
Regiment Ordinance, the Chinese Extradition Ordinance, Colony
Armorial Bearing (protection) Ordinance, and the British
Nationality (corresponding revision) Ordinance of 1981.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Discussion On Handling Existing Laws In Hong Kong (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An ordinance on electoral stipulations, the Legislative Council
(Electoral Provisions) Ordinance, and stipulations on the election
of the district and two municipal parliaments, which were
formulated by the British Hong Kong Authorities in an attempt to
apply its Constitutional Bill in violation of the Sino-British
Joint Declaration on the Question of Hong Kong, and principles
which contravene with the Basic Law and agreements and
understanding reached by the two governments contravene the Basic
Law, cannot be adopted as laws of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
The participants also held that the stipulations on explanation
and aims of the application in Clause 3 of Article 2 of an
ordinance on Hong Kong human rights, and the relevant terms and
phrases of Articles 3 and 4 of the ordinance, too, contravene with
the Basic Law and cannot be used as laws of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
Relevant stipulations in Clause 2 of Article 3 of an individual
information (secrets) ordinance, likewise, cannot be adopted as
laws of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
As for some major revisions of the original laws according to a
human rights bill, such as a revision of the Societies Ordinance
since 1992 and a revision of the Security Ordinance since 1995
also cannot be adopted as laws of the Hong Kong SAR because they
violate the Sino-British joint declaration and the relevant
stipulations in the Basic Law that the laws previously in force in
Hong Kong will basically remain unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa-Syria Arms Deal in Bidding Stage: Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Affairs
Department reiterated today South Africa's proposed sale of 638
million U.S. Dollars of tank firing control system to Syria is
still in the bidding stage at the moment.
</P>
<P>
Neither the department, nor arms supplier DENEL, nor even
President Nelson Mandela, has any doubt about that, said Pieter
Swanepoel, a spokesman for the department.
</P>
<P>
However, the local "Sunday Times" newspaper quoted some leaked
cabinet minutes as saying that the controversial deal, which has
caused an international stir in the past week, is now far more
advanced than the government has claimed.
</P>
<P>
According to the leaked cabinet minutes, the cabinet has
agreed that a pending contract should be signed to deliver the
tank firing control systems to Syria, subject to Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki's approval.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to defuse the row on the deal, the ministry
claimed earlier this week the cabinet had only given conditional
approval to the DENEL to market its products in Syria, rather
than delivery as the media reports alleged.
</P>
<P>
Swanepoel said when the contractual stage is reached, which
is only likely in about two years time, it would be necessary to
review the situation in the Middle East and decide whether the deal
should be finalized.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also reported that DENEL has spent 638,000 U.S.
Dollars on sending a team of technicians to Syria where the tank
firing control systems are fitted to the Russia-made T-72 tanks
and successfully tested in November last year.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the leakage of the cabinet minutes, Rusty Evans,
Director General of the Department, said, "this is embarrassing.
What is very serious about the cabinet documents should be a
subject of public debate even before they have been approved."
</P>
<P>
Evans also said he had never in all his years in international
affairs heard of cabinet documents being leaked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
