<HEADLINE> S. Africa Assesses Impact of Olympic Games on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 19 (Xinhua) -- A draft document aimed at
helping all South Africans, particularly those in the Cape
Metropolitan Region, assess the impact of Cape Town's bid for
2004 Olympic Games was made public today.
</P>
<P>
David Shandler, a member of the team responsible for the
Strategic Environmental Assessment (SEA) of the bid, said in Cape
Town that a public meeting on hosting the 2004 Olympic Games in
Cape Town would be held in the coming week.
</P>
<P>
The document identifies issues such as the likely impact of
the games on the economy, job creation, social development,
spatial restructuring of the Cape Metropolitan Region, public
involvement in decision-making and the natural environment.
</P>
<P>
Shandler said the document, which would be available in public
libraries throughout the Cape Metropolitan Region, drew from
reports from specialists of the SEA team as well as responses to
a questionnaire issued to the public last year.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly urge the public to look through the discussion
document, especially if they are attending the public meeting on
January 23. The success of this project depends on well-informed
public opinion," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cape Town is one of the 11 cities of the world bidding for the
2004 Olympic Summer Games. 
</P>
