<HEADLINE> Rinderpest Cases Fall Sharply in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's Agriculture
Ministry said today rinderpest cases have sharply dropped and
that most cattle have been vaccinated against the disease in the
country during the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
Seleshi Zewde, a senior veterinarian in the ministry, said
most areas of the Somali regional state in Ethiopia have
become rinderpest free zones since 1989 under an All-Africa
Rinderpest Eradication Project.
</P>
<P>
The rinderpest cases are remarkably low in other areas of
the country compared with previous years, Seleshi noted.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has about 27 million head of cattle, most of them
having been vaccinated twice.
</P>
<P>
The country is now launching a major vaccination campaign in
Afar regional state and the low-land areas along the
Ethio-Sudanese border where the disease is reportedly rampant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
