<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-19 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inter-Tajik Peace Talks End in Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The two-week long inter-Tajik
peace talks wound up here today with both parties signing an
agreement on several major issues to guarantee a lasting peace
in the Republic of Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati told reporters
after the negotiations that the peace talks in Tehran succeeded
in preparing the ground for signing the final document on
national reconciliation in the next round of talks in Tehran or
Moscow in a five weeks' time.
</P>
<P>
He voiced Iran's readiness to make every endeavor to help
restore a just and lasting peace in Tajikistan, Iran's official
news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The IRNA said, representatives of the Tajik government and the
united Islamic opposition reached an agreement on repatriation of
Tajik refugees, declaration of general amnesty by the two sides
and the procedure for forming a central commission for the
upcoming general elections.
</P>
<P>
About 700,000 people were displaced as a result of the civil
war, but most of them have now returned home.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the two sides also agreed on holding
plebiscite during the transitional period, the quota of the
opposition in the commission and restructuring the Tajik
administration system.
</P>
<P>
However, the official report gave no detail about the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the report said, the two parties held talks on
formulating the charter of the national reconciliation
commission including the number of its members, the extent of
its authority and venue for holding its sessions.
</P>
<P>
Tajik Foreign Minister Talbak Nazarov said that the Tajik
government is committed to the agreements signed in Tehran and
would fully carry out the accords.
</P>
<P>
Nazarov said "we believe that the day is coming to Tajikistan
for peace."
</P>
<P>
Akbar Turjanzadeh, representative of the Tajik opposition said
that with the signing of the agreement on repatriation of Tajik
refugees, the rights of thousands of Tajik people would be
restored and that the government has promised not to prosecute
them for their participation in the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Turjanzadeh said the opposition has pulled back its forces
from the areas singled out in the former accords and prepared the
ground for deployment of government forces, whereas, the
government has not evacuated its bases as envisaged in earlier
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Iran and Russia participated in the peace
talks as observers.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations special envoy for Tajikistan Gerd Dietrich
Merrem described the Tajik peace talks in Tehran as a
breakthrough, saying that the agreement reached between the two
parties has been a major part of a political accord.
</P>
<P>
Up to 50,000 people have died in fighting in the country since
1992, when Tajik hard-liners drove out their opponents, who then
regrouped in the rugged mountains and across the border in
Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Burundi President Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Former Burundi President
Jean-Baptiste Bagaza, a Tutsi ousted in a coup in 1987, has been
arrested, Radio Burundi reported today.
</P>
<P>
Bagaza was toppled in 1987 by Burundi's present leader Pierre
Buyoya, who had ruled until 1993 and seized power again last July
25 when he overthrew Hutu President Sylvestre Nitbantunganya in
the small central African country.
</P>
<P>
The arrest took place a day after the apprehension of
opposition Sojedem party's leader Deo Neozima, who had earlier
published an open letter attacking Buyoya's leadership, according
to a Reuter report from Bujumbura.
</P>
<P>
However, the report failed to give any reason for Bagaza's
arrest.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya, also a Tutsi, on Friday called a national debate
starting on January 28 to try to end the civil war in Burundi,
saying he wanted to listen to the opinion of everyone on peace
solutions.
</P>
<P>
He removed both hard-line Bagaza and Neozima possibly in a bid
to pave way for the national debate in the country, observers say.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of civilians, mainly Hutus, have died in
violence in Burundi over the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Burundi, controlledanya for centuries by a Tutsi minority, is
suffering severe economic problems following the imposition of an
economic embargo by neighboring central and east African states
last August in a bid to reverse the coup in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
