<HEADLINE> Egypt Renews Denial of Involvement in Letter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Postal Authority
today denied again that the letter bombs discovered in the United
States bearing postmarks of the Egyptian port city of Alexandria
were sent from Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Rafat Khlous, board chairman of the National Postal Authority,
made the statement before the People's Assembly Transport and
Communications Committee, in a report on the investigations into
the letter bombs.
</P>
<P>
Nine letter bombs disguised as Christmas cards were found at
the offices of the Arabic-language Al-Hayat newspaper in
Washington and New York and other places of the U.S. since early
this month.
</P>
<P>
The postal authority chief disclosed that Denmark announced
earlier today the arrest of the gang suspected of sending the
letter bombs.
</P>
<P>
The letter bombs that arrived in the newspaper's offices in
Washington had been thoroughly examined in New York, he said,
adding that the letters could have been laced with the explosives
later.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Bureau of Investigation had faxed five
letters bearing the postmarks of Alexandria to the Egyptian
authority for investigation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Egypt had categorically denied any letter bombs went
out of Alexandria and suggested that fake stamps can be easily
made on letters to confuse investigators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
