<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Racial Minority Men Earn Less Than Whites: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Racial minority men earn less
than whites, even when they were born and raised in Canada,
according to three studies here.
</P>
<P>
Two of the studies found visible minority men born in Canada
earned substantially less than white men, while a third study by
the federal government found a small wage gap, the Ottawa Citizen
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the study by two economists at the University of
Toronto, South Asians and blacks earned 19.9 percent and 15.7
percent less respectively than whites.
</P>
<P>
Chinese men earned 5.6 percent less, while Southeast Asians
took home about 2.3 percent less, the study showed.
</P>
<P>
Another study, by an economist and a federal government
sociologist, found that on average, visible minority men living in
cities earned 8 percent less than whites.
</P>
<P>
But the study by the federal government human resources
development indicated that visible minority men earned only about
one percent less than whites.
</P>
<P>
"We did find a gap and it's much more difficult to justify and
much more difficult to understand why it would be there for some
reason other than discrimination," one author of the studies was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The three studies are significant since they are the first to
look at how Canadian-born minorities fare in the workforce, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
And they are the first to use 1991 census data to compare the
wages of Canadian-born minorities with whites. In the 1991 census,
9 percent of adults in Canada were visible minorities, double the
number of a decade before.
</P>
<P>
More study is vital, researchers say, since visible minorities
are expected to make up to 20 percent of Canada's population by
2016. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
