<HEADLINE> Japan Donates Medical Facilities For Northwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
offered to donate medical facilities to improve medical care in
northwest China's Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
The 800,000 yuan (about 96,000 US dollars) worth of equipment
will be given to the Qinghai Provincial Hospital of Tibetan
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
A signing ceremony was held in Beijing on Sunday, attended by
Qinghai Governor Tian Chengping and the Japanese Ambassador to
China Yoshiyasu Sato.
</P>
<P>
The hospital is located in Qinghai's capital, Xining. It will
use the advanced equipment for research in traditional Tibetan
medicine, which has been used to treat disease on the
Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau for some 2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan medicine has its own theories and methods of therapy,
and is considered particularly effective in treating various kinds
diseases on the plateau.  
