<HEADLINE> Double-Digit Growth For China's Economy This Year (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- China's economy is expected to
grow 10 to 11 percent this year, economists from the State
Statistics Bureau and the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences said.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the inflation rate for retail sales will fall
further to six to seven, or "even lower than that."
</P>
<P>
The state's macro-economic control efforts have helped the
growth in the economy and the drop in inflation, they added.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth last year was 9.7 percent, down from 1992's
peaking of 14.2 percent, while inflation was 6.1 percent, down
from 1994's 21.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Rapid economic growth with low inflation will be of great
importance to China's economy," said Chen Jinhua, minister of the
State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
In analyzing inflation this year, Chen said the rate is
not likely to be too high because sufficient agriculture and
industrial products will cushion the price increase.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that last year's lagging factor for this year's
inflation rate will be of 0.5 percentage points, and that from
price adjustment of the basic products, such as petrol and
electric power, will be controlled within about one percentage
point.
</P>
<P>
According to the economists, state-owned enterprises will have
more favorable factors for development in 1997, with the help of
the state's supporting policies of increasing loans and pacing up
company merger and bankcrupcy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy to up Ten Percent (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two interest cuts last year will also encourage people to spend
more, providing a strong basis for market growth.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the government will continue to list agricultural
development as a priority. China's ambitious agriculture plan
calls for grain output to stay at last year's level of 480 billion
kilograms or to increase, and for some 12 million people to be
helped to have enough to eat and wear.
</P>
<P>
Fixed assets investment will be kept at 1996's level, much
lower than the average 34.7 percent during the Eighth Five-Year
Plan (1991-96) period.
</P>
<P>
Economists are also optimistic on world environment for Chinese
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations predicts that the world economy will grow by
3.2 percent in 1997, and world trade by 8.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
China's export volume, accounting for some 22 percent of its
GDP, is expected to increase to some extent this year.
</P>
<P>
The country is expected to use more foreign funds in 1997, the
economists said. It actually used 40 billion US dollars in foreign
funds last year.
</P>
<P>
Economists warn that some serious problems in micro-economy
development and economic structure need to merit more attention.
</P>
