<HEADLINE> Parts of China's Yellow River Frozen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Ice has covered a 1,000-km
stretch of the Yellow River, China's second longest, because of
low temperatures in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region and
Shanxi and Shandong provinces.
</P>
<P>
The period of low temperatures was 17 days earlier than normal
and 23 days earlier than last year, and flow in the frozen section
is 300 cubic meters per second, less than in previous years,
according to local experts.
</P>
<P>
Because of floods last year, the Henan section has become
shallower and is impeding the flow, causing the river to overflow
in parts of the province.
</P>
<P>
Over 40,000 local people in 47 villages there are now suffering
from the effects of this, and over 3,333 ha. of farmland and 25 km
of bank were covered as of January 13.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Yellow River Flood-Control Headquarters and
the provincial government have visited the disaster-stricken areas
and relief work is under way, according to local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
