<HEADLINE> Canadian Prime Minister Ends Visit to Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien and the mission he was leading left here tonight at the
end of a five-day visit to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
During their stay in the country, they signed 10 agreements
with the Thai government and the Thai public sector and 55
business contracts and memorandums of understanding.
</P>
<P>
The 10 inter-governmental and inter-public sector agreements,
of a cooperative nature, signified a shift in the Canadian-Thai
relationship, from a donor-recipient one to an equal partnership.
</P>
<P>
Between 1981 and 1995, Canada gave Thailand a total of 350
million Canadian dollars (266 million U.S. dollars) in official
development aid.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on investment promotion and protection is
important for future businesses for both sides for a long time to
come.
</P>
<P>
Canadian companies showed interest in investing in Thailand in
electricity generation, petroleum, resources management and
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Another important deal was the contract for Thailand to buy a
small Canadian satellite for natural resources and environmental
surveying.
</P>
<P>
The contract was saved at the eleventh hour when the Canadian
side agreed to postpone Thailand's payment for the deal and import
more Thai goods.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is facing an economic slowdown and a current account
deficit.
</P>
<P>
From a broad perspective, Chretien's visit indicated that
Canada attaches importance to the region, particularly in the
economic field.
</P>
<P>
Under the present investment protection agreement, more
Canadian investment is expected in Thailand and bilateral trade
will also increase, as Thailand would serve as a gateway for
Canadian goods to Indochinese countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
