<HEADLINE> Beijing Memorial Held for Revolutionary Martyr </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A ceremony in Beijing today
marked the 100th anniversary of the birth of Xie Zichang, who
founded a revolutionary base in the northern part of Shaanxi
Province, northwest China, in the early 1930s.
</P>
<P>
The revolutionary base later became a focal point for Communist
soldiers from other areas on the Long March, Mao Zedong's
strategic retreat to the north from 1934 to 1936.
</P>
<P>
For the ceremony, Premier Li Peng wrote: "Inherit the
revolutionary spirit of the martyr and strive for China's
modernization drive."
</P>
<P>
Liu Huaqing, a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee and vice-chairman of
the Central Military Ccommission (CMC), said on behalf of the CPC
Central Committee and the CMC, "The life of comrade Xie is
transient but glorious. He devoted his life to the revolutionary
cause, and was loyal to the people up to his death."
</P>
<P>
He called on the Party to follow Xie's example and to rally
closely around the Party Central Committee with Jiang Zemin at the
core.
</P>
<P>
"Let's work hard together to welcome the return of Hong Kong
and the Party's 15th national congress with new material, ethical,
and cultural accomplishments," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bo Yibo, a revolutionary veteran and retired senior leader,
also sent a letter to the forum in memory of Xie.
</P>
<P>
Xie was fatally wounded while defending his guerrilla base
against a nationalist attack in early 1935, and died at the age of
38. 
</P>
</TEXT>
