<HEADLINE> Japan Adopts 1.9 Percent Growth Target for Fiscal 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government today
formally adopted the lowest official economic growth target for
the country for four decades.
</P>
<P>
The inflation-adjusted 1.9 percent growth in gross domestic
product (GDP) for fiscal 1997 eclipses the previous record low of
2.4 percent for fiscal 1994, Kyodo news service reported.
</P>
<P>
The official target was announced last December by Economic
Planning Agency Minister Taro Aso but was formally adopted today
at an extraordinary meeting of the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The government predicts the economy should gradually move
toward sustained growth after a slowdown in the first half of
fiscal 1997 due in part to a rise in the consumption tax rate from
3 to 5 percent which takes effect in April.
</P>
<P>
That increase is expected to dampen consumer spending and push
the consumer price index up about 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also formally adopted its basic stance on the
conduct of economic policy, Kyodo reported.
</P>
<P>
The state budget proposal for fiscal 1997, which begins April
1, was approved by the cabinet late last year.
</P>
<P>
The government said that it would seek to ensure a
self-sustaining economic recovery, led mainly by domestic demand,
and stressed its resolve to push for deregulation and reforms in a
variety of areas, including the structure of the economy,
administration and fiscal issues, the news service said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
