<HEADLINE> Japanese Government Policy on Terrorism, Foreign Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
said today Japan will continue to seek a peaceful solution to the
Peru hostage crisis but will not bow to terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Terrorist activity is a grave challenge to all states and
societies and it is vital for the international community to
tackle terrorism in unity," Hashimoto said in a policy speech at
the first session of the new Diet (parliament).
</P>
<P>
The hostage crisis has now dragged into its 35th day with 73
hostages still held captive by a group of Peruvian rebels at the
Japanese ambassador's residence in Lima.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto reiterated Tokyo's "complete trust" in Peruvian
President Alberto Fujimori's tough stance in handling the hostage
standoff and vowed to work with the international community to get
the hostages freed as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
On Japan's diplomatic policy, Hashimoto underscored the
importance of trilateral ties between Japan, China and the United
States in the Asia-Pacific region and said Japan will seek better
ties with China while hailing improved Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
"Progress in any of the bilateral sets of relations among
Japan, the U.S. and China will contribute to the stability and
development of the entire Asia-Pacific region," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister pledged to strengthen military cooperation
between Japan and the United States by establishing new guidelines
for defense cooperation under the upgraded bilateral security
framework.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda told the Diet that
Japan's security alliance with the U.S. is the foundation of sound
bilateral ties between the two countries and that efforts are
needed to make it function more smoothly and effectively.
</P>
<P>
Ikeda also emphasized the importance of relations with China
and South Korea, saying sound ties with the two countries would be
conducive to the maintenance of peace and stability in the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
He said Tokyo will work harder to promote relations with
Beijing through close contacts and various exchange programs as
this year marks the 25th anniversary of the normalization of
diplomatic relations between Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
The minister renewed Japan's support for China's economic
reform and opening policy and reiterated that China should be
brought into the World Trade Organization at an early date.
</P>
</TEXT>
