<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Trade Volume to Exceed 300 Billion Dollars in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to have a
foreign trade volume of 310 billion US dollars this year, up 6.4
percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Wu Yi, minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Co-operation at a national conference on foreign trade in
Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that China had a record high 289.9 billion US dollar
foreign trade volume in 1996.
</P>
<P>
As for the foreign trade and economic co-operation this year,
the minister said that the policies for an active, rational, and
effective use of overseas investment should be followed this year
to raise the work to a new height.
</P>
<P>
In reviewing China's 1996 foreign trade performance, Wu
explained that two major trends were the processing trade for the
first time accounting for half the total trade volume and more
foreign funds actually being used in spite of the fewer projects
approved.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China approved more than 24,000 overseas-funded
projects, with over 42.35 billion US dollars of overseas funds
being used.
</P>
<P>
China has so far approved a total of 280,000 such projects
which used overseas investment totalling 177.2 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Wu told the local officials and leader of the country's big
trade companies present at the meeting that China's foreign trade
is facing a new situation and that the greatest difficulty will
come from blindly seeking to expand the scale and increase
quantity, a practice that was common under the centrally planned
economy.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister said, as the opening up policy proceeds,
more importance will be placed on foreign trade and economic
cooperation by local governments. And China's huge market,
abundant labor, political and social stability, market
environment, and investment climate will help create favorable
conditions for the development of foreign trade and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that China will continue its comprehensive foreign
trade strategy, which is designed to promote balanced development
in overseas investment, trade and other economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
She said that China will also give priority to rectifying trade
orders, to exploring international markets in all directions, and
to speeding up the spread of information and legislation on
foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
