<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attack on Political Leader Condemned in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Political parties in Nepal
have condemned a violent attack on a senior political leader by
activists of some parties in western Nepal last weekend, sources
said here today.
</P>
<P>
President of the main ruling Nepali Congress (NC) party Girija
Prasad Koirala was violently assaulted on Saturday afternoon in
the Baitadi district, about 400 km west of Kathmandu, after
attending a mass meeting there.
</P>
<P>
Some 90 activists from other parties chanted anti-NC slogans
and pelted stones at Koirala's helicopter when it was about to
take off, sources of the NC party said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the 75-year-old Koirala was hit by one
stone in the leg and some windows of the helicopter were broken
during the attack.
</P>
<P>
According to the NC central office here, the attackers were
from the main opposition the Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxist Leninist CPN-UML) and NC's ruling partner the National
Democratic Party (RPP).
</P>
<P>
The NC party in a statement issued here Sunday urged the
coalition government to take strong action against those who
assaulted Koirala.
</P>
<P>
However, leaders of the CPN-UML and RPP in separate statements
today also denounced the violent attack on Koirala and denied that
the attack was carried out by their party workers.
</P>
<P>
Koirala, a former prime minister who led an NC government from
1992 to 1994, was in western Nepal on his party's campaign for the
upcoming lower house by-elections.
</P>
<P>
The by-elections will be held on the coming Friday in five
constituencies throughout the country for five seats in the lower
house which are vacant currently.
</P>
<P>
The NC party has said it wants to win all the five seats in the
house to replace the CPN-UML as the single largest party in
parliament. The NC presently has 86 MPs in the 205-seat house
while the CPN-UML holds 87 seats.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
