<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Revises Foreign Exchange Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- China's State Council today
announced its decision to revise the Regulations on Foreign
Exchange, which were adopted last January.
</P>
<P>
An article has been added, saying that the state will no longer
impose restrictions on international payments and money transfers
under current account.
</P>
<P>
Another new article, the 15th, says that after a person has
emigrated from China, the profits generated by his assets within
China can be used to purchase foreign exchange at designated banks
if he can present verification and proper certificates, and the
money can be taken out of the country.
</P>
<P>
The first section of the previous 13th article, now the 14th,
has also been changed and now permits any individual in need of
foreign exchange for personal use to purchase a limited amount. If
the amount is insufficient, the person can apply to the foreign
exchange management department for approval for more.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations also combine the previous 15th and 16th
articles into one, the 17th, which has been revised to say that
any foreign institution or individual in China wishing to remit
RMB income abroad must go to designated foreign exchange banks
with proper verification and certificates.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations took effect today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
