<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Geologists Look for Environmental Protection Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- After two years' efforts by the
China's State Bureau of Environmental Protection and the Chinese
Academy of Sciences, a geo-environmental research center opened
today in Beijing, to give Chinese geologists a role in the
country's battle against pollution and other environmental
problems.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhenhua, head of the State Bureau of Environmental
Protection, said the center could provide "substantive support"
for his bureau's work, and that he hopes "more scientists can take
an active part in environmental protection, and play a significant
role in China's bid to achieve sustainable development."
</P>
<P>
Xie and Zhou Guangzhao, president of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, explained that the center will be under the "dual
leadership" of the bureau and the academy for the next ten years.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts regarded this "dual leadership" as a bold new
attempt to promote cooperation by the country's scientists and
decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
"This practice will help scientific research results to get
more official attention and better use, and give the scientists
more chances to get involved in and have an influence on the
government's decision-making process," one of the analysts noted.
</P>
<P>
Environmental geology is a science that grew out of basic
geology, and the geo-environmental research center will do
research on the China's major environmental problems, and try to
develop the country's own system of environmental theories.
</P>
<P>
It also hopes to be able to help the nation's economy overcome
major difficulties and to develop a theoretical basis and plans
for the country's large-scale environmental reforms or energy
projects.
</P>
<P>
The center will be affiliated with the Chinese Academy of
Sciences' Institute of Geology, which has over 400 researchers,
including six academicians and 53 professors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
