<HEADLINE> Nigeria To Cut Import Duties in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is
likely to cut the import duties on major categories of goods this
year, the local newspaper "Vanguard' reported today.
</P>
<P>
the measures are likely to be announced by Finance
Minister Anthony Ani at the 1997 budget breakdown in Abuja later
today.
</P>
<P>
"The slash in import duties is designed to chart a rational
course of trade policies, provide effective rate of protection
for industry and agriculture, reduce inflation and address the
problem posed by high duty rate on imported goods which have no
substitutes," government officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Major food items and raw materials will have their tariffs
reduced, said the report. But details of the plan are not yet
known.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the Nigerian government cut the import duties on
food, consumers electronics, raw materials for essential drugs
and a number of other goods by five to 50 percent in 1995.
