<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Sex Slaves Picket Japanese Embassy in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Filipino women forced
to work as sex slaves for the Japanese imperial army during World
War II held another protest rally today at the gate of the
Japanese embassy here.
</P>
<P>
Carrying banners and chanting their demands for justice, about
60 ageing Filipino sex slaves survivors, also known as "comfort
women," picketed the Japanese embassy for nearly one hour this
afternoon, pressing for official and legal compensation from the
Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
The rally is the second this month and part of the 1997
campaign launched by Lila-Pilipina, a private group representing
former sex slaves from the Philippines, to demand the adoption of
a draft compensation law for non-Japanese comfort women by the
Japanese Diet (parliament).
</P>
<P>
Amaneda Ballahabi, a representative for the protestors, urged
the Japanese government to act quickly because former sex slaves
are elderly and sick.
</P>
<P>
The 69-year-old woman, who was forced to provide sexual
services for Japanese soldiers when she was just 14 years old,
denounced an agreement signed last week by the Philippine
government and the private Japanese Asian Women's Fund (AWF).
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the AWF will allot 1 million yen (8,547
U.S. dollars) in medical and welfare assistance to every Filipino
sex slave for a period of five years. But Ballahabi said it is
state compensation and official apologies, not AWF money, that
former sex slaves want.
</P>
<P>
She said the campaign would continue until the women received
official compensation and an apology from Tokyo. Another four
rallies outside the Japanese embassy in Manila are planned over
the next two months.
</P>
<P>
During World War II, thousands of women from the Korean Peninsula,
China, the Philippines and some other Asian countries were forced into
sexual slavery by the Japanese military, who called them "comfort
women."
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, there were a total of 169 documented comfort
women, of whom about 100 are still alive now, according to Maloo
Sabado, a member of the private Philippine Asian Women's Human Rights
Council. But she said the actual number of Filipino comfort women was
much higher.
</P>
<P>
After the war, the Japanese government denied the atrocity for
decades. In 1996, it acknowledged the existence of comfort women,
but refused to give individual state compensation and make
official apologies to them.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government only admitted its moral responsibility to
the comfort women, claiming all its legal war obligations and
responsibilities, including reparations to war victims, have been
settled.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
