<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somalia's Powerful Warlords Hold First Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 20 (Xinhua) - Somalia's two most powerful
warlords, Hussein Aideed and Ali Mahdi Mohamed, today started
their first face-to-face peace talks in capital Mogadishu, aiming
to end the six-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here quoted South Mogadishu's security
officials as saying that the two leaders met at a hotel along
Mogadishu's greenline, which separates the divided city into the
north controlled by Ali Mahdi and the South by Aideed.
</P>
<P>
They said the talks are centered on reopening Mogadishu Port
and the international airport, which had been closed since 1995
because of feuds between the two factions.
</P>
<P>
A number of other issues concerning ways to maintain ceasefire
in the war-torn country are also under discussion, said the
officials. But details of the talks are not yet known.
</P>
<P>
A peace process has been going on in the Horn of African
nation since a ceasefire accord was signed by representatives of
the warlords in Nairobi, Kenya in late 1996 following the death
of late hardline warlord Mohamed Farah Aidid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Vows to Carry out Wide-ranging Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto today pledged wide-ranging reforms of the national
bureaucracy, fiscal and economic structures and the social welfare
and educational systems.
</P>
<P>
In a policy speech on the first day of the new session of the
Diet (parliament), Hashimoto said the reforms would cause great
hardship but were necessary if Japan's economy was to develop more
vigorously and thrive in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"Our current systems -- namely, administrative systems,
regulation on private-sector activities, social security and
welfare structures, educational administration, and relations
between the central and regional governments -- have in general
functioned effectively for a long time.
</P>
<P>
"However, we are now in an era when the world is rapidly
becoming integrated and when people, products, capital and
information flow freely, and it is clear that the current
framework is an obstacle to the vigorous development of our
country."
</P>
<P>
He said that to change a system that is so deeply rooted in
Japanese society "would take great hardship," but the planned
reforms in the six areas are necessary in a bid to transform the
nation's rigid social and economic system into one that can cope
with changing global trends in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto called fiscal 1997 the first step towards fiscal
reconstruction and said the government had set various
quantitative targets, including cutting central and local
government debt to 3 percent or less of gross domestic product
(GDP) by fiscal 2005.
</P>
<P>
On education, the prime minister vowed to transform the current
rigid schooling system into one which aims to develop the diverse
abilities and creativity of each individual from a viewpoint of
lifetime education.
</P>
<P>
On social security, Hashimoto said the government would allow
for more input from the private sector to create a system which
can efficiently provide high-quality services to meet users'
varying needs.
</P>
<P>
On economic reform, he stressed the need to boost funding,
technology and human resources to foster new industries and turn
the Japanese economy into one of greater efficiency, more
flexibility and competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
As for monetary reforms, he said the government would submit to
the Diet a bill to revise the Foreign Exchange and Foreign Trade
Control Law for drastic liberalization of Japan's financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
On administrative reform, Hashimoto said the government would
work to abolish government involvement in private activities,
entrust public services to private entities and promote
decentralization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
