<HEADLINE> China's First Treasury Bonds for 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- China's first group of treasury
bonds this year, with a zero-interest coupon rate, have been
issued at a price of 82.39 yuan per 100 yuan, according to the
Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The price was decided today through public bidding. The major
underwriter of the bonds, valued at 20 billion yuan (about 2.4
billion US dollars), was Haitong Securities Co. Ltd and the deputy
underwriter, Shenyin and Wanguo Securities Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The two-year bonds will be issued as of Wednesday and
redeemable at par value upon maturity on January 22, 1999. They
can be traded on the secondary securities market immediately after
the issue closes on February 17.
</P>
<P>
Individuals can buy the bonds on the country's two securities
exchanges in Shanghai and Shenzhen, the finance ministry said.
</P>
<P>
China issued more than one trillion yuan worth of treasury
bonds last year and is expected to float more this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
