<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Police Urged To Deal Firmly With Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi today told the police force to deal "swiftly and firmly" with
criminal activities, especially the rampant armed robberies and
cattle rustling.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking to senior police officers from Rift Valley
province in Nakuru where they are attending a meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan leader urged the police to be extra alert to avoid
the kind of violence witnessed during the run-up to the 1992
general elections as an electioneering fever is setting.
</P>
<P>
Moi pledged full support in recruitment of more staff and
provision of modern equipment in order to cope with the new
challenges of the complex world of crime.
</P>
<P>
He advised Kenyan policemen to cultivate moral courage, adding
that it is only through such moral courage that they will
sustain their reputation.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest report, armed crime incidents in Kenya's
capital Nairobi had risen to 470 in the third quarter of last
year compared with 331 and 373 in the first and second quarters.
</P>
<P>
Car-hijackings in the capital had reached an all-time high of
420 incidents for a three-month period ending last September, up
from 227 and 201 in the first two quarters last year.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that illegal arms trade is rampant in the
country with a range of weapons being easily purchased in
Nairobi, Isiolo, Namanga and Kiambu.
</P>
<P>
A police task force was set up in Kenya in the beginning of
this year to fight increasing armed violence in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
