<HEADLINE> Iraqi Newspaper: Sanction Is Another War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 20 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi English newspaper
today carried a signed article describing the U.N. sanctions
imposed on Iraq as "another war more serious and more devastating"
to the country.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the Gulf War in early 1991, the sanctions imposed
on Iraq for more than six years is "another war more serious and
more devastating albeit on a slower scale," said the article by
Nail al-Hadithi, Editor-in-chief of the Baghdad Observer.
</P>
<P>
"The Iraqis have been kept captive of sanctions," the article
said, adding that tens of thousands of Iraqis are suffering from
hunger or almost starvation to death since they could neither find
food, nor could they find badly needed medicines.
</P>
<P>
The author of the article complained that although the leaders
of the main big powers involved in the Gulf War declared they were
not fighting against the Iraqi people, but against the government,
the war turned out to be a large-scale attack on all facilities
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The six-year sanctions have greatly affected the Iraqis' daily
life and caused hundreds and thousands of civilian deaths, many of
them were children.
</P>
<P>
The article ended with the hope that the implementation of the
oil-for-food deal would be only the first step for the full
lifting of all sanctions imposed on Iraq since its August 1990
invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
