<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official on HK's Economic Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong, with its highly
internationally-oriented economy, is particularly outstanding in
its capability to overcome external limitations and make full use
of its various advantages.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the region is closely following trends seen in the
global economy and development, and is adjusting its economic
structure in an active and timely manner.
</P>
<P>
An Min, assistant minister for Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, made the remarks today when asked to respond to a
journalist's question on which industry in Hong Kong will be the
most competitive.
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong's manufacturing sector has been moving up on
a massive scale since 1980s, and to date, 80 percent of the sector
has been moved to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, the service sector as a tertiary industry has
developed rapidly, and its dominance in Hong Kong's economy has
been constantly solidified," he noted, adding that the growth of
this sector by far surpassed that of other countries or regions.
</P>
<P>
It accounts for over 80 percent of Hong Kong's GDP compared
with a little over 10 percent of the secondary industry --
industry and manufacturing -- and less than one percent of the
primary industry -- agriculture, he said.
</P>
<P>
"As global economic integration picks up its pace and the
Asia-Pacific economy continues to grow, I believe that Hong Kong
will continue its efforts to adjust its economic structure and
work to improve its economic environment and conditions," he
said. "This will keep Hong Kong as vibrant as it is now and
further consolidate its status as an international center for
trade, finance, shipping and information," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
