<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Enterprises Enjoy No Privileges in HK SAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese enterprises will engage
in fair market competition in the future Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), without enjoying any privileges that
are not extended to other businesses, said An Min, assistant
minister for Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a journalist's question on whether Chinese
corporations will have an advantageous position in the Hong Kong
SAR, he said today that the mainland's investment in Hong Kong
will be listed as overseas investment, under the framework of "one
country, two systems." The investment is subject to the state's
provisions applying to overseas investment, he added.
</P>
<P>
An said Chinese enterprises, when operating in a free and open
market such as Hong Kong's, are required to observe the local laws
and regulations.
</P>
<P>
As all other businesses active in Hong Kong, Chinese
enterprises should be protected and bound by local laws, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In a word, Chinese enterprises shall follow internationally
prevailing economic and trade rules and local "rules of the game,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The arbitration of all economic and trade contract disputes
shall draw reference from international practices, he emphasised.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The principles we are pursuing are fair competition,
vigorous development, operation guided by law and enriching Hong
Kong."
</P>
<P>
An said Chinese enterprises have invested considerable
investment, up to tens of billions of US dollars in Hong Kong,
which takes up 10 percent of the Hong Kong's aggregate economy and
becomes an important factor contributing to the region's economic
development and stability.
</P>
<P>
"After July 1, 1997, Chinese businesses in Hong Kong will
devote more efforts to improve quality and efficiency, engaging in
fair competition with other businesses and joining hands to
promote Hong Kong's prosperity," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
