<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Bans Cosmetic Products Containing Bovine Tissues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC)
introduced today a provisional ban on the marketing of unsafe
cosmetic products containing bovine tissues or extracts to avoid
risks for humans concerning the so-called Mad Cow Disease.
</P>
<P>
The commission bans the placing on the market of cosmetic
products containing tissues and ingredients derived from the
encephalon, spinal cord and eyes of bovine, ovine and caprine
animals.
</P>
<P>
An EC spokesman said that this ban had in fact translated into
legal terms a situation that already existed in the EU cosmetics
industry.
</P>
<P>
"It is appropriate to take measures designed to ensure the
safety and health of consumers without awaiting irrefutable proof
of the link between BSE (Mad Cow Disease) and Creutzfeldt-Jakob
Disease in humans," the commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
According to a directive of the commission, this ban is
provisional and will be reviewed in line with the development of
scientific knowledge.
</P>
<P>
EU member states are obliged to bring into force the laws,
regulations and administrative provisions necessary to comply with
this directive no later than June 30, 1997, the commission said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
