<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Warns PA Against Declaring Independent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu today warned the Palestinian Authority (PA)
against unilaterally declaring an independent state.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Israel Radio quoted Netanyahu as saying that
Israel would respond seriously to such a move, which he
described as violation of the peace accords between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Repeating earlier statements, Netanyahu added that the
establishment of a Palestinian state would hurt Israel's vital
security interests.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks following a speech by PA President
Yasser Arafat Sunday during his first victorious visit to the
West Bank town of Hebron, where Israeli troops last week
redeployed and handed over 80 percent of the city to the
Palestinian self-rule.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to about 60,000 tumultuously jubilant Palestinians,
Arafat called for continued march to the still occupied Eastern
Jerusalem and to struggle for achieving Palestinian
independence.
</P>
<P>
"Hebron is the start of the process which will bring us areas B
and C and will lead to an independent Palestinian state," he said.
</P>
<P>
But in contrast with his previous speeches marking the handover
of Palestinian towns to his control, Arafat did not emphasize
Eastern Jerusalem, which he wanted to be the capital of a future
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Following the difficult Hebron deal, Israel and the PA will
likely resume talks soon on the final settlement to
Israeli-Palestinian disputes, including final status of the
self-rule areas, Jerusalem and Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The two central disputes will be the issue of Jerusalem and
establishment of Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Israel has vowed never to concede its self-claimed
sovereignty over whole Jerusalem. Netanyahu has indicated his
willingness to expand the Palestinian self-rule, but he has
flatly rejected the establishment of an independent Palestinian
state, saying Israel must retain control over the border, space
and water resources which are so vital to its national
security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
