<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Declines in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The overall month-on-month
inflation rate decreased to 10.8 percent in December 1996 from
11.4 percent in November the same year, according to the latest
issue of the Monthly Economic Review.
</P>
<P>
The review, published by the Central Bank of Kenya, noted that
the decline in inflation was more pronounced in the lower and
middle income groups and affected almost all consumer items,
except transport, basic foods and clothing.
</P>
<P>
The review said the downward trend is likely to continue and
the month-on-month rate is expected to fall below 7.0 percent in
the next four months.
</P>
<P>
It attributed the decline to the government's adherence to a
strict fiscal and monetary policy, a stronger local currency
Shilling and a drop in prices of petroleum and petroleum-related
products.
</P>
<P>
The money supply is targeted to consistently expand by no
more than 15.7 percent between January and March this year, it
stated.
</P>
<P>
The review pointed out that the fiscal policy will be
further tightened to ensure that the ratio of the budget deficit
to GDP falls below 2.2 percent by the end of the current
financial year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
