<HEADLINE> COSCO Vows to Work Toward HK's Prosperity, Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- China Ocean Shipping (Group)
Co. (COSCO) pledged today to enhance cooperation with Hong Kong
shipowners and to devote its efforts toward Hong Kong's prosperity
and stability after mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's role as a free port and an international shipping
center will not be changed after it returns to the motherland,
said Chen Zhongbiao, president of COSCO group and chairman of the
China Shipowners Association.
</P>
<P>
At a luncheon given in his honor by the Hong Kong Shipowners
Association (HKSOA), Chen outlined the rapid growth of China's
ocean shipping industry in the last several years, as a result of
the nation's expanding foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
During the eighth Five-Year plan (1991-1995) period, China's
total trade volume was over 1 trillion U.S. dollars, with the
average annual growth at 19.5 percent. The trade volume is
expected to top 400 billion dollars in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstances, China's shipping industry, which
carries over 90 percent of foreign trade cargoes, has seen
business increase sharply, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Container turnover, in particular, has enjoyed an average
annual growth of 30 percent in the last several years, and is
estimated to reach a high of 10 million 20-foot equivalent units
(TEUs) in the year 2000, compared with 5.49 million TEUs in 1995.
</P>
<P>
With China's policy of opening to the outside world, foreign
shipping companies have entered the huge Chinese market, Chen
said. By 1995, 15 had established their wholly-owned subsidiaries
in China, in addition to 350 representative offices set up by
foreign shipowners, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The COSCO chief in his speech also hailed the establishment of
Shanghai Shipping Exchange in November 1996, which will help build
an equitable, open and fair cargo forwarding market in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Taliban Launch New Offensives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan has seen a sudden
upsurge in fighting over the past few days when the Taliban
militia launched a lightning attack against the anti-Taliban
alliance on the front north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia, which control two-thirds of Afghan
territory, are already close to the Panjshir Valley, the
stronghold of Ahmad Masood, commander of the ousted government
forces, following their capture of Kapisa Province northeast of
Kabul Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The front-line, which a few weeks ago was close to Kabul, has
now been pushed back 100 kilometers into the territory under the
control of the ousted government.
</P>
<P>
Kapisa was seized a day after the Islamic militia recaptured,
in a lightning strike, the strategic Bagram Airbase and the key
provincial capital of Charikar, which had been defended largely by
Masood's forces.
</P>
<P>
In tanks and armored personnel carriers, Taliban soldiers on
January 16 stormed the airbase, which is about 50 kilometers north
of Kabul and where the biggest military and civilian airport in
Afghanistan is located.
</P>
<P>
From Bagram the Taliban pushed northward another 10 kilometers
and took Charikar, the capital of Parwan Province.
</P>
<P>
By Saturday, the Taliban militia approached the town of
Gulbahar, about 100 kilometers north of Kabul. Gulbahar, with its
strategic location, is believed to be the gateway to the Panjshir
Valley.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban had tried to push into the Panjshir Valley after
their capture of Kabul last September, but failed despite several
costly attempts as Masood lost no time in launching a
counterattack and forced the Taliban forces to retreat to areas 20
kilometers north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The latest offensive by the Taliban came after peace talks were
held here last week among Afghan warring factions under the
auspices of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the Taliban and the anti-Taliban alliance
led by northern warlord Rashid Dostum attended the three-day
working group meeting, as termed by the head of the U.N. special
peace mission to Afghanistan, Norbert Holl.
</P>
<P>
Holl called for an immediate cease-fire among the Afghan
warring factions after the renewed fighting which he described as
all the more "disturbing."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy emphasized that a cessation of hostilities would
help promote the process of dialogue among the warring sides which
did see some positive developments at their Islamabad meeting.
</P>
<P>
Although no substantial progress was made, the factions agreed
to resume their talks in February.
</P>
<P>
However, it is believed that no major breakthrough could be
achieved through such kind of talks until the Afghan warring
factions earnestly observe an overall cease-fire.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
