<HEADLINE> World Bank Disagrees With Nigeria's New Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has expressed
reservations with aspects of the Nigerian government's 1997
budget released last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The issues of privatization and the exchange rate are in the
center of the disagreement, World Bank officials said at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is currently negotiating with the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund on its Medium Term Economic Strategy,
which is linked to the reduction of the country's huge external
debt standing at 28 billion U.S. Dollars by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank insisted on bolder steps to be taken in
privatization, but Nigerian Head of State, General sani Abacha,
said various options on privatization "will be closely examined
by a highly-powered committee before any privatization exercise
is embarked upon."
</P>
<P>
"The government will ensure effective and efficient management
of these enterprises while the nation gets maximum benefits from
service and resources," said Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank expected the Nigerian government to drop its
officially fixed exchange rate of one dollar to 22 Naira and
liberalise the exchange rate, but government insisted that the
current exchange rate system will not change in the 1997 fiscal
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
