<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official on HK's Economic Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), as a separate customs territory of
the People's Republic of China, will enjoy a high degree of
autonomy in its administrative management of the economic and
trade sector.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it can formulate and implement economic and trade
laws, policies and administrative measures on its own in strict
keeping with the principle of "one country, two systems" and the
Basic law, said An Min, assistant minister for Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
When asked by journalists to comment on how foreign investors
can be assured that Hong Kong will continue to be a society ruled
by law, An said Hong Kong will continue to enjoy a relatively
complete legislation, and the Basic Law of the Hong Kong SAR
provides a basic guarantee for its economic prosperity and stable
development.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law stipulates that after July 1, 1997, Hong Kong's
legislation will remain basically unchanged, he added.
</P>
<P>
All the existing laws will remain in force, except those
provisions that contradict the Basic Law or those requiring
amendments by the Hong Kong SAR legislature, he explained.
</P>
<P>
An noted all the central government's economic and trade laws,
regulations, policies and administration measures effective on the
mainland shall not be applied to Hong Kong, adding that Hong
Kong's agencies are by no means subordinate to their counterparts
in the central government, and Hong Kong's relevant departments
will not experience any interventions in their routine work.
</P>
<P>
"We'll continue to welcome foreigners to Hong Kong to make
investment after 1997," he pledged, "encouraging them to engage in
legal operation and fair competition."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
