<HEADLINE> Continuous Tremors Rock Areas Near Indonesia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Continuous volcanic tremors are
rocking the areas surrounding Mount Merapi, Indonesia's most
active volcano, which erupted last Friday, a volcanology official
said today.
</P>
<P>
Mas Atje Purbawinata, head of the Volcanology Office in
Yogyakarta, about 35 kilometers south of Merapi, said that Merapi,
since its eruption on Friday, has not stopped spewing heat clouds
and lava, Antara news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mount Merapi is still on the "alert" warning level, he said,
noting that at least 63 tremors and 62 major lava emissions were
recorded since Sunday evening to 6:00 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the "alert" status of the volcano, thousands of people
have returned to their homes at the slopes of Mount Merapi since
late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 2,968-meter volcano stands at the border of Central Java
province and Yogyakarta.
</P>
<P>
There was no official news on casualties but unconfirmed
reports said six people went missing last Friday when the Merapi
erupted.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's 17,500 islands are dotted by about 500 volcanoes,
127 of which are active and make up the Pacific rim of fire.
</P>
<P>
Merapi's last eruption was in 1994, when more than 60 people
were killed and dozens injured as well as thousands were forced to
flee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
