<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberian Warlords Reaffirm Commitment to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of warring factions in
Liberia have repeated their commitment to the completion of
disarmament and demobilization of their fighters before the
January 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi made the remarks at the
weekend after his visit to Liberia last week on conducting the
second phase of the verification of the disarmament,
demobilization and repatriation of the Liberian factions.
</P>
<P>
His words might be helpful to remove the fear of any new
obstacles in the Liberian peace process aroused by recent calls
from warlords Charles Taylor and Alhaji Kromah for fresh peace
talks "to thrash out unresolved issues", local observers say.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) is
greatly concerned about the current low level of disarmament,
Ikimi said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
So far only about 7,000 of Liberia's estimated 60,000 fighters
have put down their weapons since the disarmament operation began
on November 22.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to make it clear to all citizens of Liberia that
anyone found carrying arms beyond that date would be doing so on
his individual account and not on behalf of any faction," Ikim
said.
</P>
<P>
The West African peacekeeping force, known as ECOMOG, "will be
in a position to take appropriate action against such
individuals," he added.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS is determined to keep to the schedule of implementation
of the Abuja peace accord signed by factional leaders last
August, which will lead to the conduct of elections by the end of
May this year, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi said his assessment team has recommended that the
ministerial meeting of the ECOWAS Committee of Nine on Liberia be
brought forward to early February from March "to assess the
outcome of the disarmament and endorse the mode of implementation
of the rest of the program."
</P>
<P>
The minister also appealed that the international community
should not engage in any exercise that could impede the
implementation of the peace program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
