<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Civil Servants to Study Putonghua Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- About 2,000 civil servants of the
Macao Government will begin to learn Putonghua, or standard
Chinese language, this year to prepare for their future career.
</P>
<P>
That means an increase of some 800 people, compared with the
number of 1,215 civil servants who attended language training
courses in 1996, according to figures released by the Department
of Administrative and Civil Service Affairs of the Macao
Government.
</P>
<P>
The department plans to start 88 Putonghua courses and 13
Cantonese language courses this year for the civil servants who
chose to remain in Macao after 1999 when China resumes its
exercise of sovereignty over Macao.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that as most civil servants who decided to stride
across 1999 need to improve their language skills and as the use
of Chinese as an official language proceeds, the number of
Putonghua and Cantonese language courses tends to increase.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, an official of the Macao Cultural Department urged
Macao students to learn Putonghua now, saying it would be the main
form of communication in the future Macao Special Administrative
Regional Government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
