<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: HK Has to Increase High-Tech Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has to increase its
input in the development of high technology, said Herbert Liang,
chairman of the Chinese Manufacturer's Association (CMA) of Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
At a recent interview, Liang told Xinhua that in the
development of the manufacturing industry, Hong Kong has fallen
behind among "four small dragons in Asia."
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong's manufacturing industry is composed of small
and medium-sized enterprises, which lack funds and professionals
for research and development.
</P>
<P>
He said that to meet the trend on the international market,
Hong Kong has to promote high-tech industries so as to enhance its
competitiveness in the world.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the Hong Kong government set up the
Industry and Technology Development Council and Hong Kong
University of Technology in an effort to enhance high technology
development, but the impacts were inconspicuous due to
insufficient investment.
</P>
<P>
The way for Hong Kong to develop high technology is to
integrate the Chinese mainland's technological base and huge
market demand with Hong Kong's own edges, make use of the research
results of the scientific institutions on the mainland and carry
out large-scale research and development programs to create
technology-intensive industries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Liang said the CMA is committed to promoting Hong Kong's edges
in developing high value-added industries via its missions in
foreign countries and the Chinese mainland, with a view to
securing their investment in and cooperation with Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Collaboration in this regard is both beneficial and
complementary to Hong Kong and the mainland," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Liang, the CMA will spearhead, in the coming year,
assistance to local small and medium sized enterprises in
enhancing their competitiveness, exploring investment
opportunities in Central and West China and stepping up economic
cooperation between the Chinese mainland and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The association has set up a 3 million HK dollars (387,000 U.S.
dollars) Industrial Support Fund for a "Net for Small and
Medium-Sized Enterprises" on the Internet to provide on-line
market information to the enterprises and encourage wider adoption
of information technology in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On Hong Kong's economic prospect in 1997, Liang said he is very
optimistic about the economic performance of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said the CMA predicts that the economic growth this year
will surpass that of 1996, reaching 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
On Hong Kong's handover in the middle of 1997, Liang said the
current sound macro-economic environment, coupled with the picking
up of Hong Kong's economy, is conducive to the territory's smooth
transition.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China has now reached its historical moment of
enjoying a most stable social order, a booming economy and the
best diplomatic relations, which will all guarantee a smooth
transition in Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Home Study Assistance Hotline Popular </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A telephone hotline aiming to help
primary school students in their home study turned out extremely
popular in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The hotline, sponsored by the government education department,
receives more than 200 calls a day, mostly from pupils of grade
four, five and six, asking questions related to maths and English
lessons.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Education and Youth Department said that the
hotline was expanded from two lines in the beginning last October
to four by the end of 1996, and may be further increased to ten
lines or more, to meet surging demands.
</P>
<P>
The hotline is available between five o'clock to ten in the
afternoon from Monday through Saturday, with students from the
University of Macao volunteering to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
Most parents in Macao are busy with their work and have little
time helping their children's home study, prompting the
establishment of the hotline, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Macao now has some 40,000 students in primary schools, attending
courses in Cantonese, English or Portuguese language. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
