<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Several Thai Sectors Face Further Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 20 (Xinhua) -- As a result of the adverse
impact of an overall economic slowdown in Thailand last year,
several sectors of the economy may not look promising this year.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has taken a series of urgent measures to
revive the economy, but they have yet to prove effective in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
Stagnation could still be a problem with several sectors and
business people, in particular new entrants, need to be prudent in
their management, if they want to survive the sluggish period, the
Thai Farmers Research Center has warned.
</P>
<P>
The oversupply in the property sector, which has been building
up over the last three to four years, cannot be expected to be
eased within this year. The sector is faced with low buying power
and high interest rates and a recovery will hinge, to a large
extent, on the government's financial incentives.
</P>
<P>
Plastic products, whose prices have been high because of high
wages and expensive raw materials, may find it hard to compete
with products from countries where cost is lower. Quality is
another problem that could affect exports and worse still,
beginning this year the European Union has reduced by half plastic
import tariff privileges for Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Expansion of garments industry would remain slow and it is
expected to hit a record-low this year, down by five percent
further. Thai clothes will find it harder to penetrate the U.S.
market because goods of Mexico, a member of NAFTA (North American
Free Trade Agreement), are cheaper and enjoy lower tariffs.
</P>
<P>
For gems and jewelry, although their exports grew by about 9.4
percent last year, the growth rate was lower than the average 10
percent in the 1990-1995 period.
</P>
<P>
This year prospects for gems and jewelry exports are expected
to be still poor as economic growth in importing countries and
regions remains slow.
</P>
<P>
The cost of Thai gems and jewelry is high because of high cost
of cutting and machinery imports.
</P>
<P>
The general outlook for the tourism industry this year is also
poor, with tourist arrival growth expected at eight percent, but
outbound at 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The problems are old ones, such as pollution, traffic jams and
safety. Outbound tourism will continue to experience tough
competition in a declining market, and a price war is likely to
spread in the market.
</P>
<P>
Hotels will continue to suffer from an oversupply as more new
rooms are available. Main hotels in major destinations have seen
their occupancy rates drop.
</P>
<P>
Footwear is unlikely to show a brighter picture this year. Its
exports may rise about five percent, but last year the industry
recorded a major decline of 37.6 percent in comparison with 1995.
</P>
<P>
Costs, such as raw materials and labor, will continue to go up,
and the European Union's anti-dumping strategy against Thai
footwear will be another factor the sector will have to face.
</P>
<P>
Rising costs and shortage of labor may also affect the frozen
food industry and output of black tiger prawn will also drop.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors which will face a gloomy year are toys, sanitary
ware, golf courses and ceramics.
</P>
<P>
However, the research center pointed out that prospects for
canned seafood and furniture are among those which could be
promising.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
