<HEADLINE> Nigerian Professor Urges Exploitation of Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A Nigerian professor has called
for the maximum exploitation of the country's nuclear energy
potentials before its huge oil reserves are used out.
</P>
<P>
E. D. Mshelia, a professor from Abubakar Tafawa Balewa
University, said the situation that 62 percent of the country's
electricity are generated from oil must be changed.
</P>
<P>
The professor noted that Nigeria's 20 billion U.S. Dollars
worth of oil reserve could be exhausted within the next 20 years
at the present production of two million barrels a day. It must,
therefore, make haste to seek alternative sources of energy.
</P>
<P>
"The only available and viable option is to exploit the
possibility of generating electricity from nuclear sources," said
the professor.
</P>
<P>
He pictured a bleak future for the country to satisfy its
increasing demands for electricity in the forthcoming decades.
</P>
<P>
At present, Nigeria has two research bodies engaged in nuclear
research. It also has uranium mineral. In the years during the
oil boom, the country had planned to develop the nuclear
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
