<HEADLINE> Doctor Warns Increasing Hepatitis C Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The number of hepatitis C
sufferers tends to increase rapidly due to infection via tainted
blood transfusions.
</P>
<P>
Treatment for the hepatitis C virus has a low success rate and
prospects of finding a vaccine is still gloomy, today's South
China Morning Post quoted a Hong Kong doctor as saying.
</P>
<P>
Dr Nancy Leung Wai-yee, head of the Hepatology Department of
the Hong Kong Chinese University said that people have a high risk
of developing hepatitis C once infected with the virus.
</P>
<P>
Now about 0.5 percent of the population is infected with the
hepatitis C Virus, while ten percent is suffering from B virus.
But Eighty percent of carriers of hepatitis C virus may become
chronic, compared with ten to 20 percent for hepatitis B virus.
</P>
<P>
The Hepatitis C, which is transmitted through body fluids, can
cause symptoms like influenza, vomiting and high fever, said the
doctor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
