<HEADLINE> Kenya BoostS Gum Arabic Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is conducting a gum and
resin research in attempts to transform the cottage industry into
a commercial enterprise, the Daily Nation newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The research subjects include the determination of where
certain varieties of gum can be easily found to respond quickly
to potential buyer's orders.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has been depending on natural oozes in harvesting gum
arabic from Acacia Senegal, which abounds in its northern Turkana
district.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Forestry Research Institute (KEFRI) and the
Semi-Arid Lands Training and Livestock Improvement Centers of
Kenya (SALTLICK) are in charge of the research project which is
funded by Britain's Overseas Development Administration (ODA).
</P>
<P>
KEFRI and SALTLICK will carry out thorough research on
varieties of gum arabic and resins so as to determine where and
when the best quality can be harvested.
</P>
<P>
Turkana is capable of producing up to between 50 and 60 tons
of gum annually which is mainly exported to Britain, France and
Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
