<HEADLINE> Spanish Mission to Boost Trade With Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Spanish
Association of Agricultural Machinery Exporters arrived in
Malaysia today for a two-day visit to the country as part of their
mission to seek business partners in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, made up of representatives of eight Spanish
companies, will also visit other Southeast Asian countries
including Thailand and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish business people will hold individual meetings with
potential importers and distributors during their visit here,
delegation chief Aitor Santillan said today.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish companies are producers of farm equipment,
agricultural implements and machinery for cattle breeding,
sprayers and accessories, grain silos and feedmill plants,
automatic scarecrow equipment and power shafts for agricultural
machinery.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Spain exported about two million ringgit (about
800,000 U.S. dollars) worth of agricultural machinery components
and spare parts to Malaysia. Santillan said Spanish products must
compete with those from Australia, Denmark, Italy, Japan and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
But, he said there was good potential for Spanish-made stock
breeding products like automatic feeding systems, grain silos and
feedmills plants in which Spain has a competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, in 1995, Malaysia's exports
to Spain totaled 526.4 million U.S. dollars compared with 321.9
million dollars in 1994, while Spain's exports to Malaysia were
valued at 210 million U.S. dollars in 1995 against 81.1 million
dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Most of Malaysia's exports to Spain were consumer electronics,
data processing units and air conditioners, natural rubber, latex
and gloves, and palm oil and palm oil products. Spain's exports to
Malaysia included boilers and machines, automotive components,
paper, furniture and stainless steel laminated sheets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
