<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, Iraq Reach Agreement on Oil Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and Iraq have agreed on
an across-the-board price of 19.10 U.S. dollars per barrel for
Iraqi oil to be supplied to the kingdom in 1997, Jordan Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed Saturday night by the two countries
in the Iraqi capital of Baghdad, Iraq will meet Jordan's request to
raise its oil supplies in 1997 by 7 percent to reach 4.5 million
tonnes of crude oil and oil derivatives (25 million barrels of
crude and 7 million barrels of derivatives).
</P>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, Jordanian Minister of Industry
and Trade Ali Abul Ragheb and Minister of Energy and Mineral
Resources Hisham Dabbas attended the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
During the Baghdad talks, Jordan and Iraq also signed a trade
protocol, under which Jordan will supply to Iraq goods and
services worth 255 million dollars in 1997 compared with 200
million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The agreement means that Jordan will receive Iraqi oil worth
625 million dollars in 1997. The free-of-charge supply will account
for 300 million dollars, leaving 325 million dollars to be
paid. This will be settled by the 255 million dollars trade
protocol and the rest 70 million dollars will be adjusted as
partial payment of Iraq's debts to Jordan, which is estimated by
officials here at 1.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, Iraq has been providing Jordan with crude oil and
petroleum products, half free of charge and the other half at
discounted prices.
</P>
<P>
Jordan paid 15.25 dollars per barrel of Iraqi oil and
received 250 million dollars worth of free Iraqi oil supply in
1996.
</P>
<P>
In return, Jordan exported food and medicine to Iraq, but not
free of charge.
</P>
<P>
Jordan reduced its trade volume with Iraq to 200 million
dollars in 1996 from 400 million dollars in 1995, saying that the
cutback was prompted when Iraq could no longer afford to pay the
foreign exchange needed for the Jordanian goods.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's oil imports from Iraq are carried out under a special
exemption to the United Nations economic sanctions imposed on
Baghdad after its August 1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
