<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Japan Folklore Symposium Held in Kunming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The first Sino-Japan Folk
Culture Symposium has recently been held in Kunming, capital of
southwest China's Yunnan province.
</P>
<P>
Hosted by Yunnan University, co-sponsored by Japan Comparative
Folklore Academy and a Yunnan industry group, the symposium
aims to impel Sino-Japan folk culture exchange and the friendship
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Folklore study is a research to decipher the customs of
different countries in the world and to enhance the understandings
between countries of different cultures.
</P>
<P>
Cognate culture background of China and Japan supplied ample
materials for the research. Achievements have been made since
1980s as the result of the efforts by scholars of both countries.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 70 scholars attended the symposium. They handed in about
60 thesis on folklore, religion, mystery and exploitation of folk
culture resources of the two nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe To Vaccinate 4 Million Cattle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government is
planning a nationwide campaign to vaccinate about 4.2 million
heads of cattle against parasites and other diseases as part of
the effort to restore viability to the livestock industry.
</P>
<P>
Re-production of cattle in the communal areas, which formed a
good percentage of the herd in the nation, has been adversely
affected by worms and other diseases, according to Stewart
Hargreaves, director of country's veterinary services.
</P>
<P>
"We have embarked on a countrywide program to dose cattle in
the communal areas in the fight against worms," he said.
</P>
<P>
Funding for the massive program had come from the World Food
and Agricultural Organisation as most farmers in the communal
areas could not afford to vaccinate their cattle.
</P>
<P>
After the serious drought of 1991/92 had depleted the herd in
the southern African country, the government embarked on the
restocking program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
