<HEADLINE> UN Chief Pledges Aid to Nigeria's Democratization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, January 20 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said he is planning to visit Nigeria "when time is
right" and pledged to assist the country's democratization
process.
</P>
<P>
"That is how we normally operate," Annan said last weekend,
explaining that the U.N. will participate actively in the
country's electoral process if the Nigerian government makes the
request.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who is the first sub-Saharan African taking office of
the U.S. chief, said he will step up dialogue with the Nigerian
military government on the democratization process in the west
African country.
</P>
<P>
"I supported what my predecessor did I intend to continue,"
said the Ghanaian, who became the U.N. Secretary-General on
January 2 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the execution of Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other
human rights activists in November 1995, former U.S. Secretary
General Boutros-Ghali sent a U.N. fact-finding mission to Nigeria
to asses the country's democratization process and the human
rights situation.
</P>
<P>
The mission, which had visited Nigeria from March 29 to April
13, 1996, while concluding that the phased transition program,
scheduled to be completed on October 1, 1998, is "genuine",
warned against imposition of further sanctions against Nigeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
