<HEADLINE> Indonesia-Malaysia-Singapore Growth Triangle to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The
Indonesia-Malaysia-Singapore Growth Triangle (IMS-GT) will be
expanded to include five more Indonesian provinces, Malaysia's
national news agency Bernama reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Chairman of the IMS-GT (Malaysia)
Business Council Arshad Ayub today after chairing the IMS-GT Joint
Business Council meeting in Johore Beharu, Malaysia, about 370
kilometers southeast of Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government will submit its proposal of including
Djambi, Bengkulu, South Sumatra, Lampung and West Kalimantan in
the growth triangle to the IMS-GT ministerial meeting in May for
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
About 240 representatives of government and private sectors of
the three countries attended the meeting. The five Indonesian
provinces proposed as new IMS-GT members sent representatives to
the meeting as observers.
</P>
<P>
"The entry of the five provinces will further strengthen the
position of the IMS-GT," said Arshad.
</P>
<P>
The growth triangle was established in early 1990's, initially
covering Indonesia's Riau and West Sumatra, Malaysia's Johore and
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Last March, it was enlarged to include Malaysia's Negri
Sembilan, Melaka (Malacca) and Pahang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
