<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Electronics Sector Up 9 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's electronics
industry recorded a positive growth of 9 percent in 1996 despite a
year of flux on the international market, with the output totaling
around 45.1 billion U.S. dollars, the Economic Development Board
(EDB) said here today.
</P>
<P>
The country's electronics industry is expected to further grow
this year in line with global expectations, said the EDB, a
government statutory board established in 1961 to spearhead the
industrialization drive through investment promotion in
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
The Gross Value Added, a more significant indicator of the
health of the electronics industry, recorded an increase of 12
percent or about 12.14 billion U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The industry's fixed asset investment commitment for 1996 is
estimated at about 2.43 billion U.S. dollars, an increase of about
33 percent over the 1.79 billion U.S. dollars recorded in 1995,
said the EDB.
</P>
<P>
The data storage and office automation sectors of Singapore's
electronics industry posted a record output of 13.07 billion U.S.
dollars and 3.79 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, up by 29 percent
and 40 percent respectively, it added.
</P>
<P>
"The moderate growth of the electronics industry in Singapore
in 1996 was a result of a slowdown in the global semiconductor
industry being offset by the strong growth in data storage and
office automation equipment," the EDB commented.
</P>
<P>
This reflects the balancing effects of the various
sub-clusters, which need further diversification, to reduce
negatives of the industry's "boom and bust" cycles, it added.
</P>
<P>
This moderating effect is anticipated to remain a
characteristic of the electronics industry in the future, the EDB
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newspaper for Teenagers Makes Kids Little Masters of Press (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 20 (Xinhua) -- They look like experienced
newspaper reporters, they have interviewed state leaders and
Britain's Queen Elizabeth II, and their stories can be read in
every corner of China.
</P>
<P>
But unlike thousands of other Chinese journalists, their
full-time job is not writing news, but going to primary and middle
school.
</P>
<P>
The boys and girls have plenty of reasons to be proud of their
professional newspaper, named "Xiao Zhu Ren", or "Little
Master": the newspaper's circulation now exceeds one million,
making it the world's most widely-read newspaper for kids.
</P>
<P>
And it's run entirely by youngsters under the age of 15.
</P>
<P>
Many of the newspaper's "veteran" reporters have gone on to
work at some national newspapers and TV stations.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to give young people opportunities to practise news
writing and help them grow up in an all-round way," said Zhu
Jieshi, director and founder of the Shanghai-based newspaper.
</P>
<P>
When the paper was founded on July, 1983, it had only around
10,000 readers. There are more than 300 million children in China,
Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
But the four-page semi-weekly soon attracted attention from
young readers all over the country, because its stories, photos
and cartoons vividly cover teens' lives in and out of school.
</P>
<P>
"I like to read it because it talks about us," said a boy
reader in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"We always try to let our readers know how to become a master
of their own lives, not only now but also after they leave
school," noted Zhu, who was a long-time teacher.
</P>
<P>
In order to train a professional news staff, Zhu set up a
special school to teach the ABCs of journalism to the children.
</P>
<P>
At present, about 200 reporters in Shanghai and thousands of
correspondents across the country are working for the paper,
developing their skills in gathering and writing news.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Jewelers Want Incentives for Quality Uplift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Owners of Thai jewelry
factories have urged the government to grant lower duties on
machinery imports and easier and less expensive credit as
incentives for improving the quality of their products, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The country's jewelry industry needs to upgrade its factories
and technology to keep its competitive edge in the world market,
said executive members of the Thai Gem and Jewelry Traders
Association.
</P>
<P>
Installation of more modern machinery will help jewelry
companies move into the production of higher-end goods that are
expected to boost the sector's export earnings.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's jewelry exports value recorded a near double-digit
growth last year, while the country's overall exports barely
increased.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is the world's second largest jewelry producer in term
of volume after Italy.
</P>
<P>
For decades, Thailand maintained the ranking through producing
cheap silver and gold alloy jewelry for the lower market.
</P>
<P>
In the past three to five years, Thai jewelry products have
seen considerable improvement with new local design creations and
introduction of western skills, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
