<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newspaper for Teenagers Makes Kids Little Masters of Press (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I've learned to be very clear about the basic difference
between a composition and a news story - the composition can be
fictitious but the news must be true," said Chen Huizhuo, a
fifth-grader at Shanghai's Fahuazhen No.2 Primary School, who is a
reporter with the paper.
</P>
<P>
Instructed by teachers, the part-time reporters have
interviewed many people, both famous and not-so. The namelist
includes China's state leaders, the Mayor of Shanghai, Queen
Elizabeth II, astronauts, writers, engineers and fellow students.
</P>
<P>
"I think we've partially reached our goals," Zhu said,
explaining that a group of former reporters who have gone on to
work as professional journalists have been successful in their new
positions.
</P>
<P>
Some of them have been employed by local television stations
and national newspapers, such as "People's Daily", China's largest
newspaper, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some have become writers, others have held their own
photography exhibits.
</P>
<P>
China now has dozens of journalism colleges or departments of
journalism at universities and colleges to train news workers for
the country's huge press circle.  
</P>
