<HEADLINE> E.Africa To Establish Aeronautical University </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The three East African
countries, Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania, are planning to upgrade
their flying school to an aeronautical university to satisfy
increasing regional demand for pilots and plane engineers.
</P>
<P>
"East African ", the region's weekly newspaper, today quoted
David Wakikona, director of the flying school, as saying that the
university is expected to be jointly financed by the three
members of the East African Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
But it will continue to receive financial aid from the United
Nations Development Program and International Civil Aviation
Organization, he said.
</P>
<P>
The flying school, located at Soroti, about 300 kilometers
east of Uganda's capital of Kampala, was initially set up in 1971
to train pilots and aircraft maintenance engineers for the entire
Anglophone east African region.
</P>
<P>
It admits 20 piloting students per class for a 18-month
training session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
