<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Organs Forge Ties With Poverty-Ridden Guizhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Twelve government ministries
and non-Communist parties are uniting to help poverty-ridden
Guizhou Province jumpstart its economy.
</P>
<P>
Departments included were the ministries of Agriculture,
forestry and construction, the State Science and Technology
Commission, the Central Committee of the Communist Youth League of
China, Xinhua News Agency, Jiu San Society and the Chinese
Peasants and Workers Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
They have sent 39 officials to serve as deputy party and
government heads in 36 counties in a bid to improve management
expertise there.
</P>
<P>
The number of poor counties in Guizhou make up 8.1 percent of
the total number in China, and account for 12.5 percent of the
country's total impoverished population.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that poor areas in Guizhou have received 200
million yuan in financial aid from the 12 government
departments. The money has been used to build 100 projects, the
majority of which are in operation and have been initially
successful.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, the Ministry of Forestry Industry has allocated
54.79 million yuan to help 10 poor counties build 67
forest-related projects and develop forest product and fruit
processing techniques.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the output value generated from forestry by the 10
counties climbed to 578 million yuan by the end of 1995,
accounting for 26 percent of the total industrial and agricultural
output value there.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture offered 9.4 million yuan to build
22 farm produce processing firms in the mountainous area of Wulong.
</P>
<P>
With their support, the living standards of more than 3.7
million people who used to live under the poverty line, with an
annual income of less than 530 yuan per person, have greatly
improved.  
</P>
</TEXT>
