<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Self-Reliant SADC To Set up Fund for Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) is planning to establish a 50
million U.S. Dollar fund for drought relief, according to the
latest issue of "the Zambian Farmer".
</P>
<P>
The SADC is currently making a survey to determine how best
the fund can be used to alleviate drought problems in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Drought has ravaged the southern Africa in recent years and
SADC member states have found themselves lack of food to cushion
people from recurrent droughts.
</P>
<P>
"It's better to put up our own instrument which we can rely on
rather than go to donors every year asking for food aid or
emergency assistance," said SADC food security organizer Reginald
Mugwara.
</P>
<P>
The fund, expected to be operational by March this year, is
expected to come from both governments and non-governmental
organization of the 12 SADC member states.
</P>
<P>
The money in the fund will not be intended for hand-outs, but
will be borrowed at concessionary interests to help member states
import food in drought years, according to Mugwara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
