<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Rules On Listing Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- China has come up with a new
set of rules on how companies are listed on the stock exchange,
putting stricter controls on their financial disclosures, new
stock pricing, and underwriting of shares.
</P>
<P>
"The rules are designed to protect investors from falsified
information and to encourage better performers to list," one
official with the China Securities Regulatory Commission, the
industry's watchdog, explained.
</P>
<P>
Certified Public Accountants who mistakenly predict 10 to 20
percent higher earnings for a listed company will have to issue a
public apology to investors. It there is an intentional
miscalculation of above 20 percent, both the accountanting firm
and the evaluated company will have penalty levied by the
commission.
</P>
<P>
New stock prices will be based on average profits over the past
three years, rather than on an earnings forecast.
</P>
<P>
Shares held by employees of a listed company cannot be traded
for three years after the date of issue, and there is an average
limit of 5,000 shares per employee.
</P>
<P>
The nation's 300 key enterprises will be given top priority in
listing, as will companies that are using modern enterprise
systems, the rules say. Companies in the agriculture sector, and
basic energy, transportation, telecommunications, raw materials,
and high and new technology industries will be encouraged to list.
</P>
<P>
Listing of processing industries and commercial businesses will
be restricted, while the financial and real estate sector won't be
considered for fund raising through the stock market for now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
