<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Players Protest Over Heat In Australian Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Women players protested to the
Australian Open officials over the heat-wave conditions, delaying
a start to their matches in Melbourne on Monday.
</P>
<P>
With temperatures soaring to near 40 Celsius -- and over 50
Celsius on court -- a number of players sought to have the Extreme
Weather Conditions rule invoked which would have given them 10
minutes breaks between the second and third sets.
</P>
<P>
But tournament referee Peter Bellenger rejected their
arguments, saying it would be unfair for those who were forced to
play in equally hot conditions yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Top women's seed Steffi Graf and third seed Conchita Martinez
yesterday wilted in the conditions and both lost. Graf was
whisked away for treatment after she was defeated by Amanda
Coetzer in the 4th round match.
</P>
<P>
Belgian player Sabine Appelmans received treatment for more
than two hours and another player had to be placed on an
intravenous drip.
</P>
<P>
The men's players also complained about the hot wave. "It is
too hot, you can't run, if you do after 10 minutes you are dead,"
said Croatian third seed Goran Ivanisevic after he beat Norway's
Christian Ruud to reach the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Men's second seed Michael Chang also had difficulty in the
conditions, although not as much as his beaten opponent Andrei
Medvedev. Chang reached the quarter-final yesterday.
</P>
<P>
In the first round of the tournament, which was played in
similar conditions, defending champion Boris Becker said he had
been scared to run at times during his match because he felt he
would tear the skin from his feet.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the Australian Open moved from the grass courts
Kooyong to the new National Tennis Center in 1988, players have
complained about the heat generated on the concrete based Rebound
Ace courts.
</P>
<P>
Tournament officials would not budge from their "no relief"
stand when it comes to hot weather. The roof of the center court
stadium can be closed to protect the players, but tournament
 policy is that outdoor conditions should be maintained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
