<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Draws Rosy Picture for Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- China has drawn a rosy picture
for its cultural development in the 21st century, saying it will
be a time for prosperity and greater social and economic
achievement.
</P>
<P>
According to a plan issued today concerning cultural
development by 2010, the sector should be put under the guidance
of the Party leadership in the next century and it must have an
explicitly socialist focus.
</P>
<P>
The ambitious outline, written by the Ministry of Culture,
states that a powerful management and operations mechanism will be
created in the sector, and that the funding channels set up for
cultural development will be greatly improved by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The plan stresses the expansion of cultural exchange between
the inland areas, Hong Kong, Taiwan and Macao, vowing to send more
artists to the territories and set up foundations to support the
activities.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, the plan says, China will build an electronic
information network on the subject of culture, as well as a large
number of key theaters and museums that can reflect the country's
rising status in the world.
</P>
<P>
Cultural facilities will be built throughout the country, and
various forms of the arts and literature will engage in
competition. People can enjoy top-rated artistic performances and
other cultural works in a clean and healthy market.
</P>
<P>
The plan suggests that more cultural laws and regulations be
drafted, and that the sector should be more involved in beneficial
economic interests. People are expected to spend more money on
culture and become consumers of cultural goods.
</P>
<P>
It indicates that China's fine literature and arts should be
further spread around the world.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, China will cultivate 100 artistic
and literary masters and a number of experts who can administer
the sector well, according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, another 500 historical sites will be included on
a list to receive state protection in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
The outlines states that the cultural management system must
stay in line with the socialist market economy, meet the
requirements of socialist ethical and cultural progress, and be
governed by the laws of culture itself.
</P>
<P>
The sector's development in the next century must be guided by
Marxism, Leninism and Mao Zedong Thought, as well as Deng
Xiaoping's theory on building socialism with Chinese
characteristics, and it should follow other culture policies set
by the Party, such as "let a hundred flowers blossom and a hundred
schools of thought contend".
</P>
<P>
The outline urges Chinese people to carry forth the fine
tradition of their culture, and to import fine foreign
culture. Any decadent cultural element in the market must be
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the outline will help create new splendor for
the 5,000-year-old Chinese civilization, and bring China into the
next century with a brand new image, said Liu Zhongde, Culture
Minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
