<HEADLINE> Government Army, Rebels Build up Forces in Mindanao, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Tension remains high in Buldon
town, Western Mindanao, as Philippine government troops and Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebels are building up their
forces following heavy skirmishes there last week, official
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
At least six people, including two soldiers, died and several
others were wounded in last week's clashes triggered by an ambush
by 50 MILF rebels against government soldiers, who were setting up
checkpoints along the road to Buldon.
</P>
<P>
The official Philippine News Agency said today that no new
clashes were reported in Buldon during the past three days, but
shelling and sporadic bursts of gunfire could still be heard in
the area.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Noel Detoyato, a spokesman of the government
army, as denying that the shelling comes from government troops.
</P>
<P>
"It is the enemy that is mortar shelling our troops," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the deployment of additional government troops in Buldon,
Detoyato said that the military buildup is not intended for a new
offensive against the MILF but for "security purposes" only.
</P>
<P>
However, Al Haj Murad, MILF vice chairman for military affairs,
was quoted by the agency as saying that government troops have
been continuously bombarding them with 105mm howitzers.
</P>
<P>
"The blasts do not come from mortars but from howitzers and we
do not have those kind of artillery. Only the government soldiers
have those," he said.
</P>
<P>
Murad also warned that unless immediate steps are taken to ease
the tension in the area, the on-going peace negotiations could be
adversely affected.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MILF started peace talks and entered
into an informal truce earlier this month. The next round of peace
talks is scheduled for next month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
