<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Airways Denies Neglect of Safety Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A senior executive of Thai
Airways International (Thai) has denied that Thai has neglected
aviation safety standards.
</P>
<P>
Thamnoon Wanglee, president of Thai, insisted that his
company's safety record is up to standard.
</P>
<P>
He said Thai strictly follows the U.S. aviation standards and
its safety standards have been approved by the U.S. Federal
Aviation Administration (FAA).
</P>
<P>
Thamnoon made these remarks when commenting on a report that
the Australian Civil Aviation Safety Authority was not happy with
Thai's safety measures.
</P>
<P>
However, a Bangkok Post report today quoted a Thai Airways
International source as saying that Australians' doubt about
Thai's safety standards are not totally groundless as the current
management of Thai, the national flag carrier, has not paid enough
attention to safety standards.
</P>
<P>
The source cited lack of a fair overtime pay system and lax
discipline among maintenance staff for the obvious result.
</P>
<P>
Thai is among airlines from 15 countries, mostly from Latin
America, which the Australians have given notice to improve their
air safety discipline and maintenance quality.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia and the Philippines are the other two ASEAN members
on the Australian list.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen other international airlines have been banned from
operating in Australia as a penalty for not meeting the
authority's standards, which are based on an assessment by FAA,
the air safety regulator of the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Flights to Australia are reportedly Thai's only profitable
long-haul services.
</P>
<P>
On European destinations, at a time when even European airlines
are running at a huge loss, Thai has only maintained its aviation
rights to wait for the European union's economy to pick up, the
Bangkok Post quoted a European airline's representative in
Thailand as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Thai lost its flights to four north American
destinations -- two each in the U.S. and Canada, because of low
profitability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandans Kill Airport Runway Birds To Protect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Entebbe International
Airport is waging a campaign of wiping out birds on the runway
to put safety of human life ahead of environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
"Losing 300 lives of passengers in a plane crash is a greater
concern to the government. I want the birds to leave and go
somewhere. But when they approach the runway they should be
killed," Transport Minister John Nasasira said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The birds were reported to be originating from a fish landing
site near the airport where they carry fish wastes to eat on the
runway, while some were attracted to eat worms in the overgrown
grass on the runway.
</P>
<P>
On January 10, 1997, a Uganda Airline plane made an emergency
landing shortly after take-off when its engine sucked two marabou
stocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
