<HEADLINE> Mediation Meeting on Qatar-Bahrain Row Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A mediation committee of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) has ended its 3rd meeting on
improving the Bahrain-Qatari row in the Qatari capital of Doha.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Arab Emirates' news agency reported
earlier today that during the meeting held Sunday, the committee
discussed a draft memorandum of understanding among the GCC member
states and a proposal on improving the relations between Qatar and
Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
However, no details of the two documents have been released.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was convened after the mediation committee, which
groups Saudi Arabia, Oman, Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates,
failed to persuade the two neighbors to end their dispute over
the sovereignty of Hawar islands located in the Gulf in two
previous meetings held in Saudi Arabian capital Riyadh earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
The committee left Doha shortly after the meeting and headed
for Bahrain for a two-day visit in a bid to continue its efforts
to help improve Bahraini-Qatari relations.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain and Qatar has been at odds over the Hawar islands for a
decade, Bahrain was angered after Qatar took the dispute to the
International Court of Justice in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Ties between the two countries were further strained after
Bahrain accused two Qataris of spying and boycotted a GCC summit
held in Doha in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
