<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lanka, India Strengthen Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The economic and trade ties
between Sri Lanka and India are expected to be further
strengthened as Indian External Affairs Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral arrived in Colombo Sunday to co-chair the third session of
the Indo-Sri Lanka Joint Commission.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have enjoyed closer economic and trade ties
ever since the establishment of the Commission in 1991 at
Colombo's proposal.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the Commission has played an active role,
through regular meetings, to enrich bilateral relations in all
dimensions -- economic, commercial, scientific, technical and
cultural.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka and India have witnessed larger volumes and wider
ranges of trade between them in recent years, reflecting
increasing business cooperation and commercial contacts. The
bilateral trade hit the historic record of 500 million U.S.
dollars in 1995-1996.
</P>
<P>
While India's exports to Sri Lanka constituted a large portion
of the two-way trade, there was a healthy trend indicating a
narrowing down of the trade gap, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
A number of Indian companies have been actively seeking to set
up joint ventures in Sri Lanka in areas of cement, steel,
pharmaceuticals and hospital projects.
</P>
<P>
A new joint venture -- Kiriya Milk Industries -- is being
created as part of the cooperation efforts in the dairy industry
in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The emphasis of the bilateral trade has been moving from
commodities to software technology and computer programming.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, the two countries will soon
enter into an agreement on the construction of a ground receiving
station after India provided radiosonde equipment to Sri Lanka,
</P>
<P>
At Colombo's request, the Indian government gave Sri Lanka 100
computers and accessories worth about 250,000 U.S. dollars last
September.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that the computers, installed in 10 centers
across the island country, are making available otherwise costly
computer education to the needy sections of the Sri Lanka society.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation in tourism is also booming. Sri Lanka's Tourist
Board opened a branch office in New Delhi last year as the board
expects tourist traffic from India to be an important contribution
to narrowing the trade gap between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A 40-member delegation of Indian tourism operators visited
Colombo last August and discussed with their Sri Lankan
counterparts ways to enhance cooperation and make tourism travel
between the two countries more attractive and affordable.
</P>
<P>
A large number of Sri Lankans visit India every year for
pilgrimages, medical treatment, education and business.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' national flag carriers -- the Indian
Airlines and the Air Lanka -- have agreed on Air Lanka's using the
excess capacity of Indian Airlines on a commercial basis.
</P>
<P>
Several private Indian airlines have entered into commercial
agreements with travel agents in Sri Lanka for bookings and
reservations, paving the way for more people-to-people contacts.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
