<HEADLINE> China, UNICEF Work Together on Young Girl Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and United Nations
experts will discuss strategies to help young girls in China's
poverty-stricken areas at a seminar scheduled to open next month
in southwest China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the China Children and Teenagers' Fund (CCTF)
said here today that officials from the United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) would hear reports on China's work in the adoption
of newborn girls, crackdown of child-kidnapping, social protection
of orphans, and the nutrition and education of poor girls.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Shuqin, deputy secretary of CCTF, said that fund sponsors
hope the money will work successfully to protect young girls'
rights, provide health care and education for young girls, and
offer social support for young girls' growth.
</P>
<P>
The seminar will be sponsored by UNICEF and organized by CCTF
and the All-China Women's Federation. UNICEF officials plan to
brief participants on the situation of young girls in the world's
poor areas.
</P>
<P>
According to latest statistics, 2.1 million girls between the
ages of seven and 11, most of them living in rural or remote and
poor areas, have poor chances to go to school. In China, two out
of every three dropouts are girls.
</P>
<P>
The CCTF launched the "Spring Bud" Plan in 1992 to help these
girls, raising funds from at home and abroad to put them in
school. Since it was launched, the program has aided about 430,000
girls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
