<HEADLINE> "Spring Bud Project" to Help More Girl School Dropouts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The "Spring Bud Project,"
sponsored by the China Children and Teenagers' Fund, will help
50,000 more young female school dropouts this year, according to
an official with the fund.
</P>
<P>
Fund sponsors plan to collect seven million yuan (840,000 US
dollars) to help 150,000 poor girls across the country receive
their elementary education, said Cheng Shuqin, the deputy
secretary of the fund.
</P>
<P>
Each year, when the 50,000 girls who are benefiting from the
project graduate from primary school, the fund will select another
50,000 dropouts to support, she said.
</P>
<P>
Sponsors will also set up a special fund this year to provide
professional training for the poverty-stricken girls who have
already graduated from the primary schools, said Cheng.
</P>
<P>
Since its beginning in 1992, the project has helped more than
300,000 girl dropouts in 28 provinces, cities and autonomous
regions.
</P>
<P>
But insufficient funding is still a major problem for the
project: the young people's fund received 3.63 million yuan
(440,000 US dollars) in donations last year, which was far from
enough.
</P>
<P>
The head of the fund has called on people from all walks of
life and social organizations both at home and overseas to
actively support the "Spring Bud Project." 
</P>
</TEXT>
