<HEADLINE> S.African Armymen To Take Part in Arctic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- South African armymen
will for the first time take part in defense exercises in the
Arctic Circle region, local daily "the Star" reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Two South African officers, together with German, British and
Danish troops, will hold manoeuvres, code-named "Exercise
Aadneram" in the Stavanger area of Norway next month.
</P>
<P>
The manoeuvres are being sponsored by the Reserve Officers'
Association of South Africa (ROASA) following an invitaion from
the Norwegian reserve officers' organization, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time in more than 40 years that South
Africans will have participated in exercises under conditions
such as those experienced in the Arctic.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegians are reportedly to supply the South African
participants with winter combat uniforms, skis and other
necessary equipment.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for ROASA was quoted as saying that "Exercise
Aadneram will be conducted under very harsh conditions, with snow
more than a meter deep and temperatures of minus 25 degree
centigrade.
</P>
<P>
Special forces of North Atlantic Treat Organization (NATO) and
the U.S. marines have undertaken regular cold weather exercises
in the region, the spokesman added. 
</P>
