<HEADLINE> Dhaka May Agree to Major Demand of Tribal Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
considering to form a regional council instead of the present
three local government councils in Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) to
meet the major demand of that area's tribal rebels, informed
sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Buddhist Chakma rebels, named as Shanti Bahini, have been
fighting a bush war since 1973 for autonomy of the resource-rich
hill forests in southeast Bangladesh bordering India and Burma.
</P>
<P>
The new government of Sheikh Hasina has held two rounds of
talks since last December with the Parbatya Chattagram Jana
Sanghati Samity (PCJSS), the political wing of the Shanti Bahini.
</P>
<P>
The PCJSS in their five-point demand seeks autonomy for the
regional council of the CHT and expulsion of Muslim settlers from
the plains.
</P>
<P>
The third round of talks is expected to be held on January 25
in the capital city of Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting in Dhaka is the manifestation of the confidence
that has been built between the two sides recently, about the
possibility of resolving the problem," said an official from the
special affairs division, which is in charge of the CHT affairs.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
