<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changzhou Citizens Say Goodbye to High-Fluorine Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Some 2.2 million citizens
of Changzhou and people in its surrounding areas in north China's
Hebei Province will no longer have to put up with a high fluorine
content in their drinking water thanks to the building of the
Dalangdian Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir, some 20 kilometers south of the city, began
storing water Sunday from the Yellow River via the Grand Cannel.
</P>
<P>
With the sharp decrease in surface water resources, Changzhou
was forced to explore large amounts of non-tested water
underground for daily use in local households, industrial and
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 300,000 local people were poisoned by varying
levels of fluorine.
</P>
<P>
Concerned with local residents' health, the provincial and city
governments started construction of the reservoir in February of
1995, using 380 million yuan (47.5 million U.S. dollars) of funds.
</P>
<P>
It is one of China's largest reservoirs in the plain area, with
the water storage capacity of 100 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
It can annually provide 52.6 million cubic meters of water for
household use and industrial production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Animals Face Imminent Danger in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALTAY (Xinjiang), January 20 (Xinhua) -- Hungry wolves and
harsh weather are responsible for the deaths of more than 1,500
rare animals in the Altay Prefecture of northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Of the dead animals, 30 species are listed under second-class
state protection. Officials said wolf attacks have increased as a
result of heavy snowstorms over the past 10 days which have cut
off most of the food sources in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
The number of red deer is decreasing due to cold, starvation
and the wolf killings. Twenty red deer have been found dead in the
Gobi Desert.
</P>
<P>
Severe weather has weakened more than 100 Mongolian wild
donkeys and gazelles, which are under the top state protection.
</P>
<P>
To guide wildlife protection, the regional government has set
up a special group to visit areas where wild animals have been
trapped by heavy snows.
</P>
<P>
Wildlife protection authorities have warned that large numbers
of the rare animals will die if they remain in the area much
longer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
