<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Political Interests Leave Philippine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Congress resumes
its regular session today after a four-week Christmas recess, but
differences in political interests between the two chambers are
likely to leave the country without a 1997 budget for another one
or two weeks.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, a national budget is normally passed by the
House of Representatives and the Senate in time for the president
to sign it into law well before the beginning of the budget year
on January 1.
</P>
<P>
But this year, the congress ran into trouble over the budget as
the House of Representatives has refused to accept the cuts in the
Countrywide Development Funds proposed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
The deadlock over the budget shows that the campaign fever has
already taken hold of the congress even though the general
elections are still 17 months away, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippines' constitution, members of the House of
Representatives are elected through local congressional districts
while senators are elected on a national basis.
</P>
<P>
As the representatives' popularity usually depends on budget
allocations for infrastructure funds for their districts, they
have to use the Countrywide Development Funds, or "pork barrels,"
to ensure their re-election.
</P>
<P>
However, for the senators, they rely more on campaign donations
than on pork barrels to get re-elected.
</P>
<P>
To seek their own political interests, members of the two
chambers have taken different stances on the pork barrels.
</P>
<P>
The Senate has proposed a 40-percent cut in the allocation for
the Countrywide Development Funds. But the House has rejected the
Senate's proposal, and is pushing for a 12.5-million-peso (470,000
U.S. dollars) pork barrel for each congressman, instead of the
7.5-million-peso (280,000 U.S. dollars) fund proposed by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
Senator Ernesto Herrera, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, told reporters recently that he believed the House
could eventually accept the Senate version of the budget because
the representatives will suffer more with the elections just
around the corner.
</P>
<P>
"We maintain our position that we will not restore the cut
unless they (representatives) can convince us that the restoration
would result in the greater good of the public," he said.
</P>
<P>
But his counterpart in the House of Representatives, Rolando
Andaya, thinks otherwise. "Why cut these funds which have been
included in the president's budget? The president has approved
this. It did not come out of thin air," he said.
</P>
<P>
The deadlock over the 1997 budget may continue until either the
Senate or the House makes a concession, which means that the
government is not likely to get a new budget soon, the analysts
predicted.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, Philippine law secures a reallocation of the
previous year's budget funds if no new budget has been approved,
so salaries and other recurring expense are being covered.
</P>
<P>
But without a national budget, no funds for the nation's new
projects can be released, threatening to delay 20 billion pesos
(759 million U.S. dollars) of domestic and foreign-funded
infrastructure spending.
</P>
<P>
Economists here warned that the budget deadlock may delay some
projects by five to eight weeks and push them close to the rainy
season, which could drastically increase costs.
</P>
<P>
In a worst case scenario, they said, this could mean a
100-billion peso (3.8 billion U.S. dollars) or roughly
five-percent drop in the country's gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The budget deadlock has aroused strong reactions in the
country. Some critics said that as the pork barrel gives the
incumbent congressmen a huge and unfair advantage over their
challengers, congressmen are seeking their own interest at the
expense of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
With members of the congress showing no signs of making a
compromise, the budget is unlikely to be passed before the end of
this month, analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
