<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Evacuees Back to Indonesian Volcano Despite Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of evacuees have
returned to their homes on the slopes of the Merapi volcano in
Indonesia's Central Java province, ignoring danger warnings by the
authorities, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Officials said about 15,000 evacuees from four villages in
Klaten district all returned home by late Saturday and started to
clean up the ashes.
</P>
<P>
Scores of men and women even returned to their daily chores in
the hamlets of Turgo although lava continued to spew from the
2,968-meter high rim of the volcano, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The highest settlements are some four kilometers from the peak,
said officials.
</P>
<P>
Turgo was one of the hardest hit places when Merapi erupted in
1994, killing more than 60 people and forcing thousands to flee.
</P>
<P>
By the time of the report, experts still maintained the highest
warning level of the "alert" status for Merapi, which erupted last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Experts have warned that the unstable lava topping the crater,
estimated at around 1.3 million cubic meters, could break up at
any time.
</P>
<P>
There was no official report on casualties but unconfirmed
reports said six people went missing last Friday when Merapi
erupted.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's 17,000 islands are dotted by some 500 volcanoes, of
which 127 are still active and make up the Pacific rim of fire.
</P>
<P>
Merapi is one of the most active volcanoes in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
