<HEADLINE> Thai Ad Spending Rises by 10.3 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Thai companies' advertising
spending on the media totaled 42 billion baht (1.68 billion U.S.
dollars) last year, up 10.3 percent from 1995, according to the
latest statistics released by Khoo Khaeng Data Bank here.
</P>
<P>
However, the growth rate was lower than the figure of 16
percent recorded in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Ad spending by the real estate sector posted 5.4 billion baht
(216 million U.S. dollars), down 20.5 percent in 1996 due to the
economic slowdown in the country, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the real estate sector, which spent 6.8 billion baht
(272 million U.S. dollars) on advertising, was a leading
contributor to the Thai ad industry.
</P>
<P>
The sector remained the leading category last year, followed by
alcoholic beverages, automobiles and office automation equipment.
</P>
<P>
Alcoholic beverages companies spent 2.29 billion baht (91.6
million U.S. dollars) on advertising in 1996, while the automobile
industry spent 1.79 billion baht (71.6 million U.S. dollars), and
office equipment category was at 1.58 billion baht (63.2 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ad spending of skin care products and shampoo came close in the
sixth and seventh places last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
