<HEADLINE> China to Improve Cultural Conditions for Rural Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese vice-minister of
culture has stressed that the country will have to work harder to
offer cultural activities to a large number of children in
poverty-stricken villages who have limited access to such
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 "Culture Gardens" will be created by the year 2000 at
the village or township level, in an attempt to provide rural
children with entertainment facilities, films, books, sports and a
means of education.
</P>
<P>
Each "garden" will cover a floor space of several thousand
square meters and serve as a cultural center in the region.
</P>
<P>
"China has 370 million children, and 80 percent of them live in
rural areas, distant mountainous areas or ethnic minority
regions. Their cultural undertakings are quite backward," the
Vice-Minister of Culture Li Yuanchao said at an annual work
meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the youngsters do not have enough places where
they can engage in cultural activities. They also read few books,
watch few films, and have no effective channels to enjoy modern
entertainment as their urban counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Culture has been carrying out a program called
the "Dandelion Project" to help battle these difficulties. So far,
21 experimental culture spots have been set up in 18 provinces and
autonomous regions. Another 28 are being constructed, with an
investment of more than 100 million yuan (12 million US Dollars)
allocated from the government budget.
</P>
<P>
Li also urged that practical systems through which kids can be
exposed to culture be created in most counties and villages by
2000, which will be directly providing services to rural children,
including regular film screenings and artistic performances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
