<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debt Service Ratio Drops to All-Time Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' debt service
burden declined to an all-time low of 11.6 percent last year, an
indication that the management of the country's debt has improved
over the years.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Central Bank governor Gabriel Singson was quoted
today by local press as saying that "in other words, the country's
capacity to pay grew at much rapid pace than the growth in the
foreign debt".
</P>
<P>
The debt service burden, or the ratio of foreign debt payments
to total export earnings, is an important indicator being looked
at by foreign investors and creditors as well as international
credit rating agencies as it shows the country's ability to pay
its maturing foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
Singson credited the improvement in the debt service to the
robust growth of the country's exports industry during the past
few years, which steadily sliced the ratio from a staggering 38
percent in 1982 to 11.6 percent of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Statistics Office, exports in
November grew by a record high of 30 percent, with the
January-November surge hitting 18 percent to 18.66 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, Singson said, the country's foreign debt problem is
still worrisome. He added that it had totaled 37.9 billion U.S.
dollars as of June last year according to the latest data
available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Tides of Rural Migrants to Shenzhen Ebbing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Spring Festival is
approaching, but at the Shenzhen Railway Station it's business as
usual -- unlike past years, when shoulder-to-shoulder crowds of
rural passengers squeezed onto trains to hurry home for the
Chinese people's most important holiday of the year.
</P>
<P>
The vanguard city of China's reform and opening, which first
attracted the "gold rush" of rural workers from across the rest of
the country, has been the first to see a change in the tide of
travel.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen observers attributed the phenomenon of fewer travelers
to the fact that the country's wealthiest city has adjusted its
industrial structure to dramatically reduce its need for unskilled
workers. And the central government's program for the
trans-regional migration of rural laborers has also contributed to
the lower numbers.
</P>
<P>
Most importantly, the narrowed economic gap between coastal
areas and inland provinces makes Shenzhen a less-coveted
destination, say officials and experts in Shenzhen and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
After Shenzhen, formerly a fishing town bordering Hong Kong,
was chosen as China's first special economic zone in the 1980s to
experiment with reform and opening, it instantly became an ideal
site for millions of fortune-hunters in the country, including a
large proportion of farmers.
</P>
<P>
In less than three years since 1985, over one million people
across the country flocked there, "causing extreme pressure on the
new city's ability to maintain its public order, public
transportation and public health infrastructure," said Huang
Jingrong, a labor official with the Shenzhen government.
</P>
<P>
A farmer from the inland province of Sichuan clearly recalls
his experiences. "After each Spring Festival, all the railway
stations and ports are packed with passengers heading south," he
said. "Nearly everybody took for granted that once you were in
Shenzhen, you were bound to make a fortune even by picking up
garbage."
</P>
<P>
However, of the scores of his fellow Sichuan citizens who came
to Shenzhen, only a few stayed on. The others returned home,
disappointed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
