<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Tides of Rural Migrants to Shenzhen Ebbing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To curb the random population in-flow, the local government in
1990 created a work permit system and asked newcomers to pay for
their right to residence here.
</P>
<P>
When the tides of rural workers spread to other parts of the
country, the central government introduced Shenzhen's successful
practices to them. And later on, Shenzhen drafted a local law
which proclaimed that anyone who intends to work there must have
at least nine years of compulsory education.
</P>
<P>
Starting from last year, the labor-intensive industries in
Shenzhen have been replaced by the industries of communications,
information and others which are capital and technology
intensive. Migrant workers with limited educational backgrounds
have to work elsewhere, the Shenzhen labor official Huang said.
</P>
<P>
And at the same time, the central government's national program
to oversee the orderly migration of rural laborers also helped to
ease the pressure on Shenzhen, said Zhang Xuwu, a researcher with
the Labor Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, now in full swing across the country, rural
surplus laborers must be organized by local governments to work
elsewhere, in accordance with the needs of labor markets. Most of
them are encouraged to work in township enterprises near their
homes.
</P>
<P>
The increased investments to inland areas in recent years, and
especially the township enterprises that are springing up
everywhere, have helped create more job opportunities for the
rural laborers, said an official with the State Statistical Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Investments by the central government, overseas businessmen and
coastal areas to the inland provinces in 1996 jumped by more than
18 percent over the previous year, and township enterprises have
taken in 126 million workers, accounting for over half of the
surplus laborers in the country, statistics from the bureau show.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the registered rural laborers in Shenzhen have
decreased sharply from three million in 1994 to 1.79 million in
1995; the number is much less in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"My fellow citizens no longer think Shenzhen is the only place
to make a fortune," the farmer from Sichuan said. "Some are
becoming better-off without leaving home."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
