<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines, US Settle Dispute Over Garments Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Washington and Manila have
finally reached a resolution on the long-drawn trade dispute over
the United States' new rules of origin affecting the Philippines'
garments export sector.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines accepted the United States' offer of increasing
the country's garments quota by 50 million U.S. dollars, instead
of the 40 million U.S. dollars provided earlier, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Trade Secretary Cesar Bautista was quoted as saying
that "We are happy to have reached a satisfactory solution on the
issue".
</P>
<P>
According to him, the settlement spares critical export
products such as jeans from the rules, but provides non-critical
sectors like manufacturers of polyester and shirt products no
reprieve.
</P>
<P>
However, Bautista expressed optimism the affected sectors would
be flexible enough to produce other export-oriented garments and
textile products and thus, surviving the change in rules.
</P>
<P>
The rules of origin, which was implemented by Washington last
July, stipulated that finished garments exported to the US would
be credited against the quota of the country which manufactured
the fabric.
</P>
<P>
The rules sent the Philippines' garments industry into a
tailspin, threatening to wipe out the whole industry because most
manufacturers in the sector depend on raw materials from other
countries or regions.
</P>
<P>
Its ill effects on the economy became evident when the
country's garments exports to the US went on a steady decline last
year, with total shipments to quota countries including the US,
European Union and Canada slowing down by an average of 5.4
percent to 1.9 billion U.S. dollars as of end-November 1996.
</P>
<P>
The settlement on the dispute had eluded the Philippine
government for months. Last year, it raised a protest over the
U.S. rules before the Textile Mediation Board of the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijingers to Have More "Comfortable Housing" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has completed a total
of 600,000 square meters of "comfort housing" last year, reported
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government expected to build another 600,000
square meters of the same type of housing this year, said Xu
Yinpei, chief architect of Beijing Urban Development and
Construction Corp.
</P>
<P>
The "Comfort Housing Project" is a government program aimed at
building more houses for low- and medium-income, and poorly housed
urban residents.
</P>
<P>
It is an important step in China's housing reform program,
which helps increase the living space of those with less than four
square meters of space per person, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project in Beijing's northeastern
suburbs of Wangjing Town was completed last week.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that nearly 9,000 residents will move into new
flats by the end of the June when additional interior decorating
-- which was delayed because of cold weather -- is finished, Xu
said.
</P>
<P>
Covering an area of 1.5 hectares, the current largest plan of
the project in the city can provide 260,000 square meters of
housing.
</P>
<P>
The project's design has been recognized as the best in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
All 260,000 square meters of housing are heavily subsidized by
the local government. Sales of these houses will be managed by the
local government instead of real estate and other commercial
companies, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's housing reform, workers are encouraged to
buy the flats they occupy, which state-owned enterprises sell at
below cost.
</P>
<P>
Preferential prices will be fixed by the local government. It
is estimated that a suite of 70 square meters could cost residents
140,000 yuan (16,870 US dollars), Xu said.
</P>
<P>
In the past 18 years, Beijing has built a dozen residential
districts. Housing projects like Tuanjie, Jinsong, Shuangyushu and
Fangzhuang have been completed, while dilapidated houses in
downtown area have been renovated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
