<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Protests Moscow Mayor's Unfriendly Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The unfriendly remarks made by
Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov on the Sevastopol issue cast a shadow
over the relations between Ukraine and Russia, the Ukrainian
Foreign Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
When visiting the city of Sevastopol on January 17, Luzhkov
said "Sevastopol was, is and will always be Russian territory."
</P>
<P>
"Such remarks made by Russian officials, including Luzhkov,
will be never acceptable," the Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
What the Moscow mayor said would spoil Ukraine's territorial
integrity, which has been recognized by the international
communities, including Russia, the ministry added.
</P>
<P>
Sevastopol, the major base of the Black Sea Fleet, has been
claimed both by Moscow and Kiev after the collapse of the former
Soviet Union in 1991. The dispute has worsened the bilateral ties
since legislators quarreled over the status of Sevastopol in
December 1996.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the note, the ministry reminded Moscow of the
necessity to maintain normal relations and to avoid similar
remarks in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
