<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Record for China's Shipbuilding Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- China built 1.9 million tons of
ships in 1996, hitting a new record in annual shipbuilding output,
latest statistics from the China State Shipbuilding Corporation
(CSSC) show.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.6 million tons of vessels were exported last year
to countries and regions including Norway, Hong Kong, Iran,
Canada, Japan, and Singapore, accounting for 84.7 percent of the
total.
</P>
<P>
Another 330,000 tons of ships went under construction in 1996,
and the building work is continuing this year, corporation
authorities say.
</P>
<P>
The CSSC had shipbuilding orders of 146 vessels with a combined
capacity of 2.27 million tons. Included were 81 export ships,
totalling 1.32 million tons, and 49 ships for domestic customers,
with a combined 950,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the corporation signed contracts of ship products
with an aggregate value of more than 14 billion yuan, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the amount of shipbuilding orders for CSSC was a bit
lower than in 1995, when the figure reached 2.48 million tons.
</P>
<P>
"Considering the overall performance of the world shipbuilding
market, the CSSC still became more competitive in 1996," said Li
Junfeng, an engineer of the Production Bureau of CSSC.
</P>
<P>
Two large shipbuilders, Japan and the Republic of Korea (ROK),
started a "price-cutting war" in 1996. Japan took advantage of the
drop in the Japanese yen's exchange rate to accept large
quantities of shipbuilding orders, and the ROK also took measures
against the move.
</P>
<P>
As a result, competition in the international shipbuilding
market became more fierce, increasing the difficulty for CSSC to
accept orders, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the negative factors, the CSSC still reports
further expansion of its international market, with countries such
as France and Switzerland placing orders for ships for the first
time, he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the contractual value of CSSC's export
vessels reached a combined 1.45 billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
