<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sacrificial Horses Unearthed in Central Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUOYANG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists unearthed
36 sacrificial horses dating back to the Eastern Zhou Dynasty (770
B.C. -- 256 B.C.) in the past two months in the city of Luoyang,
bringing the total number of these kinds of horses to more than
100.
</P>
<P>
The skeletons of horses were found in four ancient tombs in the
suburbs of Luoyang, which was the capital of the Eastern Zhou. The
largest tomb, which is three-meters deep and 60 sq.m. in area,
contains 24 horses. Archeologists found all the horses in the tomb
were facing south in four rows to form an honor guard.
</P>
<P>
Another 10 horses in a neighboring tomb were also arranged in
ranks.
</P>
<P>
Nine sacrificial horse tombs have been discovered so far in the
city, the largest of which has 32 horses.
</P>
<P>
A number of pieces of pottery, personal ornaments made of clam
shell and bronze, and animal bone pipes were also discovered in
the tombs.
</P>
<P>
Very close to the horses' burial place, a mausoleum of the
Eastern Zhou Dynasty was excavated, and a great number of
bronzeware, such as tripods, swords, knives, and dagger-axes
discovered.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists say that the horses were a burial offering of the
city's aristocrats, who lived in an age of belief in supernatural
powers worship and sacrifice of live victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Improving Environment for Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGDONG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province, next to Hongkong, is focusing efforts on improving the
environment for tourism instead of construction for "Visit
China '97".
</P>
<P>
During a meeting on tourism recently, Guangdong's Vice-Governor
Liu Weiming pointed out that an obstacle hindering further growth
in tourism is no longer inadequate tourist facilities and scenic
spots as it was in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
"Why can Hongkong and Singapore attract so many tourists? It's
because of their ideal service and friendly environment," the
vice-governor pointed out, urging the province to consider
improving the environment a long-term goal.
</P>
<P>
Lu Weixiong, the director of the provincial Tourism Bureau,
called on the tourist agencies to make an effort to upgrade
service.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Guangdong had 6.9 million overseas tourists, a rise
of 10.1 percent over the previous year, of which 1.3 million were
foreign tourists, an increase of 10.2 percent, and earned 2.6
billion US dollars from international tourism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
