<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-19 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Condemns Ethiopian Attack on Its Territories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Sudan today renewed its
condemnation of Ethiopia's attacks on its land amid reports of
days of massive military buildups on its southern border.
</P>
<P>
The attacks violated the principles of good neighborliness and
the provisions of the Organization of African Unity and the UN
Charter, said a statement of the Sudanese Foreign Ministry
released by the Sudanese Embassy here.
</P>
<P>
The statement warned Ethiopia against the consequences of its
adventures and the its threats to the security and safety of the
African continent.
</P>
<P>
It appealed to the international community to stand witness to
Ethiopia's breach of the related principles and conventions.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has also accused Ethiopia, Eritrea and Uganda of
supporting its rebel forces, but all the three countries have
turned down the charge.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has poor relationship with neighboring countries. The
Cairo-Khartoum ties were cool since Egypt accused Sudan of having
orchestrated the 1995 failed attempt on the life of Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and granting asylum to Egyptian extremists.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Mubarak Saturday has refused to offer support to
Khartoum and interfere in the current crisis, a request made by
Sudanese Vice President Zubair Mohamed Saleh during his unexpected
visit here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's MENA news agency today quoted the Sudanese opposition
National Democratic Rally sources as saying that its forces killed
about 150 Sudanese government troops in the southern areas under
its control during a fierce battle that broke out in the morning
and is still raging.
</P>
<P>
There has been no confirmation of the figures by the government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the opposition leader Mohamed Osman Mirghani said he
expected escalation of present confrontations in the Blue Nile
province and the eastern and southern regions in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
In a statement upon his departure here today for Jedda on a
private visit to Saudi Arabia, Mirghani said the coming stage will
witness constant escalation in diplomatic action and international
forums against the present government in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports reaching here have revealed a military
buildup of 3,000 soldiers backed by 20 heavy military vehicles in
northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The troops headed for Torit city in southern Sudan, which is
the former political capital of rebel leader Gohn Garang before
the Sudanese government forces drove him out in the early
nineties, according to MENA.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a prominent Sudanese military source that the
Sudanese armed forces take into consideration of all information on
military buildups on the eastern borders with Eritrea and Ethiopia
besides Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
