<DOCNO> XIE19970120.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Rampant in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Severe drought is towering
over Somaliland, the self-declared republic that split from
Somalia in 1991, where many wells are dry, a report from Hargeisa
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Neighboring ethiopia and nearby Kenya are all affected by the
latest drought, which aid workers say is already raising fears of
famine.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Hargeisa said Somaliland is now hard hit by
drought, with many wells and bore-holes dry and others running
out of water. Pasture land there has been devastated and former
grazing areas are now deserted.
</P>
<P>
In many areas the price of a barrel of water has risen more
than seven times and is beyond the reach of many nomadic herdsmen
whose cattle and goats are dying in large numbers, they said.
</P>
<P>
Somaliland, which has not been recognized by other states,
today appealed for urgent assistance to counter drought affecting
large areas of the Horn of Africa. It covers the area of the
former British Somaliland, which joined its southern neighbor
Italian Somalia to form the independent Republic of Somalia in
1960.
</P>
<P>
The Somaliland drought relief committee held meetings last
week with representatives of the U.N. and other aid
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Majdi Dawabi, operations officer of the U.U. Children's Fund
(UNICEF), said after the meetings, ``the drought is occurring on
an almost annual basis. We need to find a long-term solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
